{"title_page": "Sword of Vengeance (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2014 film by Jim Weedon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =  Sword of Vengeance \n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| director = Jim Weedon\n| producer = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Rupert Preston\n*Huberta Von Liel\n*Milos Djukelic <br />(<small>co-producer</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance (2015) - Cast & Crew |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Sword-of-Vengeance#tab=cast-and-crew |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n*Allan Niblo\n*James Richardson\n*Nigel Williams\n*Matthew Read <br />(<small>executive producers</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\" />\n*Milos Ivosevic\n*Ivana Panic <br />(<small>line producers</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\" />\n}}\n| writer = Julian Unthank\n| story = Matthew Read\n| starring = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Stanley Weber]]\n*[[Annabelle Wallis]]\n*[[Ed Skrein]]\n}}\n| music = [[Stephen Hilton]]\n| cinematography = August Jakobsson\n| editing = Tommy Boulding\n| production companies = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Vertigo Films]]\n*Red Production\n}}\n| distributor = Protagonist Pictures<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=http://protagonistpictures.com/film/sword-of-vengeance/ |website=Protagonist Pictures |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2014|10|10|[[Sitges Film Festival|Sitges]]|2015|03|05|[[FEST (Belgrade)]]|2015|05|29|[[United Kingdom]]}}\n| runtime = 87 minutes\n| country = [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[Serbia]]\n| language = English\n| budget =\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Sword of Vengeance''''' (Serbian: '''''Ma\u010d osvete''''')<ref name=\"IMDb\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance (2015) Release Info |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3622332/releaseinfo?ref_=ttfc_sa_1 |website=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> is a 2014 British-Serbian [[historical drama|historical]] [[action film]] directed by Jim Weedon, his first feature film, and starring [[Stanley Weber]], [[Annabelle Wallis]], and [[Ed Skrein]]. Weedon's action sequences, and the overall look of the film, were inspired by [[samurai films]]. While the action sequences and Weber's performance were reasonably well received by critics, most felt the film's dialogue and overall story were subpar, with the caveat that aficionados of the genre would appreciate it far more.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn [[Northern England]], about 1089,<ref name=\"FiS\">{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' (2013) |url=http://www.filminserbia.com/sword-of-vengeance-2013/ |website=Film in Serbia |publisher=[[Serbia Film Commission]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> some twenty years after the [[genocidal]] \"Harrowing\" (the [[Harrying of the North]] ordered by [[William the Conqueror]] to quell a series of rebellions), a former slave and [[Normans|Norman]] [[princeling]] has taken the name Shadow Walker ([[Stanley Weber]]) upon returning to his father's former lands. There the earl Durant ([[Karel Roden]]) rules as a [[despotism|despot]] with his equally cruel sons Lord Artus (Gianna Giardinelli) and Lord Romain ([[Edward Akrout]]).\n\nShadow Walker makes common cause with and rallies a large band of exiled rebel [[Anglo-Saxon]] farmers led by Anna ([[Annabelle Wallis]]). \nDurant is his treacherous uncle, who murdered his own brother and [[usurpation|usurped]] the power of the earldom, his nephew's [[hereditary title|birthright]]. One way or another, the question will be decided through battle.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Annabelle Wallis 2017.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Annabelle Wallis]] in 2017]]\n{{Castlist|\n* [[Stanley Weber]] \u2022 Shadow Walker \n* [[Annabelle Wallis]] \u2022 Anna\n* [[Ed Skrein]] \u2022 Treden\n* [[Dave Legeno]] \u2022 Osgar \n* [[Karel Roden]] \u2022 Durant  \n* [[Edward Akrout]] \u2022 Romain\n* Gianni Giardinelli \u2022 Artus \n* Peter J. Chaffey \u2022 Lucan\n* Nenad Pecinar \u2022 Kenway   \n* Milica Jevtic \u2022 Udela  \n* Misa Beric \u2022 Marin  \n* Vid Krkeljic \u2022 Wann  \n* Vahidin Prelic \u2022 Pestilence  \n}}\n\n==Genre and influences==\n''Sword of Vengeance'' is influenced by [[samurai films]] and the [[Hollywood]] [[western movies]] and [[spaghetti westerns]] which  evolved from them.<ref name=\"Scheck\">{{cite journal |last1=Scheck |first1=Frank |title=Jim Weedon's sword-and-sandals epic is set in 11th century England after the genocidal campaign of William the Conqueror |journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=18 March 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sword-vengeance-film-review-782816 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Director Jim Weedon has been a fan of the ''[[chambara]]'' style from childhood: \"I was intrigued with the idea of creating a medieval world that tonally sat within this style. Immediately we gave the film a very distinct and unexpected look and style.\"<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Alton (interviewer) |title=Interview: Jim Weedon, Director Of Sword Of Vengeance |url=https://battleroyalewithcheese.com/2015/06/interview-jim-weedon-director-of-sword-of-vengeance/ |website=battleroyalewithcheese.com |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=2 June 2015}}</ref> The influence of ''chambara'' is particularly evident in the [[choreography]] of the sword fights:<blockquote>Often when watching medieval sword fights they become tedious, clumsy and dull. Whereas the samurai films with their shorter swords lent themselves to... much faster and action orientated aspects in any given fight sequence... I was constantly looking for quick kills, sword slices that were hard and fast for the visual impact and to give us the energy and excitement of the battles as the heroes cut through cipher after cipher.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Production==\n''Sword of Vengeance'' was produced by [[Vertigo Films]] and Red Production, \"which has a long tradition of cooperation with foreign productions\".<ref name=\"FiS2\">{{cite web |title=Filming of the movie Sword of Vengeance completed today in Serbia |url=http://www.filminserbia.com/news/filming-of-the-movie-sword-of-vengeance-completed-today-in-serbia-2/ |website=Film in Serbia |publisher=Film in Serbia Commission |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Vertigo producer Huberta Von Liel noted that except for a few leading actors, the director, and the director of photography, everyone else involved, about 150 cast and crew, were from [[Serbia]].<ref name=\"FiS2\" />\n\n===Background===\nJim Weedon began his career as a film editor, and was encouraged to try directing by [[Ridley Scott]].<ref name=\"Sitges\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://sitgesfilmfestival.com/eng/film?id=10003528 |website=[[Sitges Film Festival]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> While ''Sword of Vengeance'' was his first feature film, this was \"after cutting his teeth editing music videos and television commercials.\"<ref name=\"Scheck\" /> He had won awards for his previous work.<ref name=\"Hunter\">{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Allan |title=Sword Of Vengeance |url=https://www.screendaily.com/sword-of-vengeance/5078750.article |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=17 October 2014}}</ref> Weedon was approached by Von Liel, who asked if he would be interested in making a period [[revenge]] drama: \"I was incredibly interested in the opportunity but also the fact that Vertigo Films allowed me total creative control visually.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n===Writing and characterisation===\nWhen Julian Unthank joined the project to develop the script, he and Weedon \"stripped back the dialogue to a minimum, something that was used a fair amount in the Spaghetti Westerns.\"<blockquote>We didn't want the film to fall into the standard cinematic tropes, although the script is a basic premise of revenge we wanted the story to unfold in more unexpected prose, especially the ending. I also wanted our hero to be an antihero, rather than the man that saves the day. His character although conflicted tries to atone for his sins but it comes too late, however, his absolution from Anna in the final scene allows him to find peace and solace from his chosen path of revenge.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Design===\nAesthetically, Weedon went for what he called a \"bleach bypass approach\" to [[colour grading|grading]] \"to achieve very little colour in the film.\" Wardrobe was designed to be \"muted,\" working with blues, greys and black; \"the only real colour coming through is the inherent hues from the fur that the heroes wore.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" /> The film's already low colour palette was accentuated by [[principal photography]] taking place in winter, as Jennie Kermode notes; everything appears dark, the sky a \"miserable grey,\" and the land \"hard and unyielding.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite web |last1=Kermode |first1=Jennie |url=https://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/sword-of-vengeance-2015-film-review-by-jennie-kermode |title=''Sword Of Vengeance'' |website=eyeforfilm.co.uk |publisher=Eye For Film (UK) |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Weedon said he wanted the film to \"look and smell of the dark ages.\"<blockquote>Every aspect of the film from locations to clothing had to look worn, beaten and broken. I had shot some commercials in Serbia and found that they had very talented crew in all departments. Milos Djukelic had just co-produced ''Ironclad 2'' so was ahead in terms of the requirements we needed to create this harsh and foreboding world.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Filming and editing===\nLocation scouting took place in July 2013.<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> ''Sword of Vengeance'' was filmed in thirty days in four locations in [[Serbia]].<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> These were the forest of Boj\u010dinska \u0160uma,<ref name=\"FiS\" /> in the [[Progar]] area of [[Belgrade]], as well as the fortress in [[Kalemegdan]], [[Deliblato]] and Pancevo Reva.<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> Weedon said he lost half a [[Stone (unit)|stone]] (seven [[Pound (mass)|pounds]]) the first four weeks into the shooting schedule, which was five to six days a week, in harsh weather, wading through mud every day, and later it snowed: \"days and nights were spent knee deep in mud that at dawn was dangerously frozen ice and by mid morning a muddy mass that was equally harsh.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" /> However, the most difficult part was actually the first two days:<blockquote>Ridiculously we decided to shoot the opening sequence which involved rain fx, horses, stunts, and prosthetics. It was the crew's first two days together, suddenly we are in the rain with actors who can't ride, horses that won't stand still, actors who are going into hyperthermia, and prosthetic limbs that refuse to come apart properly, add in stunts that could only be repeated three to four times, blood that wouldn't squirt sufficiently and the opening crane move into scene that kept breaking down. I did ask myself how the hell did I get into this mess.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\nWeedon described the editing of the film with Tom Boulding as \"incredibly fast\".<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n===Sound and music===\nWith so little dialogue in the film, it fell to the [[sound design]]er, Roland Heap, and the composer, [[Stephen Hilton]], to \"convey the unsaid.\" Weedon wanted the audience to have a \"musical roller-coaster ride\": \"Sound is integral to my commercial work and something that always creates the unexpected in the visuals.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n==Release and reception==\nThe world premiere of ''Sword of Vengeance'' took place at the [[Sitges Film Festival]], where it was in competition, on 10 October 2014.<ref name=\"Sitges\" /> It had its Serbian premiere on 5 March 2015 at the [[FEST (Belgrade)|Belgrade International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |url=http://2015.fest.rs/Movies/1983/Sword-of-Vengeance.shtml |website=2015.fest.rs |publisher=FEST 43rd International Film Festival |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The British theatrical release did not follow until 29 May.<ref name=\"IMDb\" />\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Sword of Vengeance'' has been available on DVD and DVD/Blu-ray (Well Go USA Entertainment,<ref name=\"RT\" /> [[Universal Studios Home Entertainment]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword Of Vengeance [Blu-ray + DVD] |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Sword-Vengeance-Blu-ray-Stanley-Webber/dp/B00V72RPLM |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> and streaming services ([[Google Play]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://play.google.com/store/movies/details/Sword_of_Vengeance?gl=no&hl=en&id=TXDQtbnE8ng |website=[[Google Play]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> [[iTunes]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://itunes.apple.com/jo/movie/sword-of-vengeance/id1005046805 |website=[[iTunes]] |publisher=[[Apple, Inc.]] |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> [[Hulu]])<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Brett |title=What\u2019s Streaming on Netflix Tonight: \u2018Acts of Vengeance\u2019 + More |url=https://decider.com/2018/01/25/new-on-netflix-acts-of-vengeance/ |website=Decider |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> since May 2015.\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Stanley Weber 2018.jpg|thumb|[[Stanley Weber]] in 2018]]\nThe [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] assigns ''Sword of Vengeance'' a rating of 13% based on eight reviews.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/sword_of_vengeance |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Critics gave faint to fair praise to the fight scenes, and to [[Stanley Weber]]'s performance, but found the film wanting otherwise, though acknowledging at the same time that the fighting sequences would be enjoyed by action film fans.\n\nAllan Hunter's review following the world premiere at Sitges set the tone for critics into 2015:<blockquote>The only things that appear to be lacking is an original story and some decent dialogue... Stanley Weber's Shadow Walker is very much in the Eastwood tradition down to the squint in his eye and the poncho-like garment draped over his strapping shoulders. He is a man with no name but a remarkably good hair stylist to maintain those immaculate cornrows... The plot is pretty basic but served up with some style by Weedon... His vision of England is bleak, oppressive and uniformly monochrome.  It sometimes seems as if the only colour in the palette of cinematographer August Jakobsson is the crimson of fresh blood. There is a good deal of blood though as limbs are hacked off, throats are slit and eyes plucked out with merry abandon.  Weedon keeps it tight and spare but the real drawbacks are the weary plotting and cheesy dialogue.<ref name=\"Hunter\" /></blockquote>\n\nFrank Scheck, writing for the ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', opines that the title \"pretty much says it all\": there are \"enough clanging sword fights, severed limbs, slit throats and bare-bones dialogue to satisfy genre fans while pretty much failing to provide something of interest to anyone else\"; the film, while \"admirably stylish\", has the feel of an 11th century-set [[video game]]. Stanley Weber stands out among the cast, \"even managing to make such declarations as \"Vengeance is my only belief\" sound convincing.\"<ref name=\"Scheck\" /> Josh Oakley complains that the dialogue is \"overwrought and bland, with the actors apparently instructed to take long pauses between each line\" and \"much of the cast\" seem to have accents like [[Tommy Wiseau]]'s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oakley |first1=Josh |title=\"It is he who brings them hope.\" |url=http://cutprintfilm.com/reviews/sword-of-vengeance/ |website=CutPrintFilm |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=17 March 2015}}</ref> Ernest Hardy of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said the fillm \"hits its mark of being a popcorn action flick just fine.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/sword-of-vengeance |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nJames Luxford of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' said there is a \"brutal simplicity to the action that will appeal to some,\" but otherwise, ''Sword of Vengeance'' \"seems stretched even for a relatively short film.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Luxford |first1=James |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |journal=[[Radio Times]] |date=May 28, 2015 |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/dhgf5q/sword-of-vengeance/ |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Jennie Kermode assigned the film 2 stars out of 5, saying the fight scenes were uneven but: \"Weber's work is carefully choreographed and will please fans of fighting films even if it does sometimes take liberties with physics. This is important because there really isn't much else in the film at all.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\" /> Geoffrey Macnab of ''[[The Independent]]'' agreed: \"The ritualised action sequences work well enough. It's just a pity the film-makers did not pay as much attention to the plotting as to the design of the movie.\"<ref name=\"Macnab\">{{cite news|first1=Geoffrey |last1=Macnab |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/sword-of-vengeance-film-review-dialogue-is-sparse-in-this-historical-revenge-drama-10282922.html|title=Sword Of Vengeance, film review: Dialogue is sparse in this historical revenge drama|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 May 2015|accessdate=2015-11-07}}</ref> Mike McCahill, writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', found the film \"perversely watchable\" and \"modest post-pub fun\"; while it is a \"low-budget\" ''[[Game of Thrones (TV series)|Game of Thrones]]'' \"cash-in\", it at least improves upon its producers' previous effort, the \"risible\" ''[[Hammer of the Gods (2013 film)|Hammer of the Gods]].''<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCahill |first1=Mike |title=Sword of Vengeance review \u2013 perversely watchable Game of Thrones cash-in |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/28/sword-of-vengeance-review-game-of-thrones-cash-in |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nCritics at ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' and ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]]'' characterised the film as a \"daft\" [[slasher film|slasher]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clack |first1=David |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |journal=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=May 26, 2015 |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/sword-of-vengeance |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lea |first1=Andy |title=Review: Sword Of Vengeance (15) is a blunt historical slasher |url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/movies/review-trailer-sword-vengeance-15-17359254 |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]] |date=May 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.metatube.com/en/videos/267263/Sword-of-Vengeance-Official-Trailer-2015/ Official trailer] on MetaTube\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJQlBW6TTi8 Official trailer] on YouTube\n*{{imdb title|3622332}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|sword_of_vengeance}}\n\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Serbian films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:British action films]]\n[[Category:Serbian action films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 11th century]]\n[[Category:Serbian historical films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2014 film by Jim Weedon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name =  Sword of Vengeance \n| image =\n| image_size =\n| caption =\n| director = Jim Weedon\n| producer = \n{{Plainlist|\n*Rupert Preston\n*Huberta Von Liel\n*Milos Djukelic <br />(<small>co-producer</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance (2015) - Cast & Crew |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Sword-of-Vengeance#tab=cast-and-crew |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n*Allan Niblo\n*James Richardson\n*Nigel Williams\n*Matthew Read <br />(<small>executive producers</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\" />\n*Milos Ivosevic\n*Ivana Panic <br />(<small>line producers</small>)<ref name=\"Numbers\" />\n}}\n| writer = Julian Unthank\n| story = Matthew Read\n| starring = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Stanley Weber]]\n*[[Annabelle Wallis]]\n*[[Ed Skrein]]\n}}\n| music = [[Stephen Hilton]]\n| cinematography = August Jakobsson\n| editing = Tommy Boulding\n| production companies = \n{{Plainlist|\n*[[Vertigo Films]]\n*Red Production\n}}\n| distributor = Protagonist Pictures<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=http://protagonistpictures.com/film/sword-of-vengeance/ |website=Protagonist Pictures |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|df=y|2014|10|10|[[Sitges Film Festival|Sitges]]|2015|03|05|[[FEST (Belgrade)]]|2015|05|29|[[United Kingdom]]}}\n| runtime = 87 minutes\n| country = [[United Kingdom|UK]], [[Serbia]]\n| language = English\n| budget =\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Sword of Vengeance''''' (Serbian: '''''Ma\u010d osvete''''')<ref name=\"IMDb\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance (2015) Release Info |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3622332/releaseinfo?ref_=ttfc_sa_1 |website=[[IMDb]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> is a 2014 British-Serbian [[historical drama|historical]] [[action film]] directed by Jim Weedon, his first feature film, and starring [[Stanley Weber]], [[Annabelle Wallis]], and [[Ed Skrein]]. Weedon's action sequences, and the overall look of the film, were inspired by [[samurai films]]. While the action sequences and Weber's performance were reasonably well received by critics, most felt the film's dialogue and overall story were subpar, with the caveat that afficionados of the genre would appreciate it far more.\n\n==Synopsis==\nIn [[Northern England]], about 1089,<ref name=\"FiS\">{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' (2013) |url=http://www.filminserbia.com/sword-of-vengeance-2013/ |website=Film in Serbia |publisher=[[Serbia Film Commission]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> some twenty years after the [[genocidal]] \"Harrowing\" (the [[Harrying of the North]] ordered by [[William the Conqueror]] to quell a series of rebellions), a former slave and [[Normans|Norman]] [[princeling]] has taken the name Shadow Walker ([[Stanley Weber]]) upon returning to his father's former lands. There the earl Durant ([[Karel Roden]]) rules as a [[despotism|despot]] with his equally cruel sons Lord Artus (Gianna Giardinelli) and Lord Romain ([[Edward Akrout]]).\n\nShadow Walker makes common cause with and rallies a large band of exiled rebel [[Anglo-Saxon]] farmers led by Anna ([[Annabelle Wallis]]). \nDurant is his treacherous uncle, who murdered his own brother and [[usurpation|usurped]] the power of the earldom, his nephew's [[hereditary title|birthright]]. One way or another, the question will be decided through battle.\n\n==Cast==\n[[File:Annabelle Wallis 2017.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Annabelle Wallis]] in 2017]]\n{{Castlist|\n* [[Stanley Weber]] \u2022 Shadow Walker \n* [[Annabelle Wallis]] \u2022 Anna\n* [[Ed Skrein]] \u2022 Treden\n* [[Dave Legeno]] \u2022 Osgar \n* [[Karel Roden]] \u2022 Durant  \n* [[Edward Akrout]] \u2022 Romain\n* Gianni Giardinelli \u2022 Artus \n* Peter J. Chaffey \u2022 Lucan\n* Nenad Pecinar \u2022 Kenway   \n* Milica Jevtic \u2022 Udela  \n* Misa Beric \u2022 Marin  \n* Vid Krkeljic \u2022 Wann  \n* Vahidin Prelic \u2022 Pestilence  \n}}\n\n==Genre and influences==\n''Sword of Vengeance'' is influenced by [[samurai films]] and the [[Hollywood]] [[western movies]] and [[spaghetti westerns]] which  evolved from them.<ref name=\"Scheck\">{{cite journal |last1=Scheck |first1=Frank |title=Jim Weedon's sword-and-sandals epic is set in 11th century England after the genocidal campaign of William the Conqueror |journal=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=18 March 2015 |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/sword-vengeance-film-review-782816 |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Director Jim Weedon has been a fan of the ''[[chambara]]'' style from childhood: \"I was intrigued with the idea of creating a medieval world that tonally sat within this style. Immediately we gave the film a very distinct and unexpected look and style.\"<ref name=\"Williams\">{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Alton (interviewer) |title=Interview: Jim Weedon, Director Of Sword Of Vengeance |url=https://battleroyalewithcheese.com/2015/06/interview-jim-weedon-director-of-sword-of-vengeance/ |website=battleroyalewithcheese.com |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=2 June 2015}}</ref> The influence of ''chambara'' is particularly evident in the [[choreography]] of the sword fights:<blockquote>Often when watching medieval sword fights they become tedious, clumsy and dull. Whereas the samurai films with their shorter swords lent themselves to... much faster and action orientated aspects in any given fight sequence... I was constantly looking for quick kills, sword slices that were hard and fast for the visual impact and to give us the energy and excitement of the battles as the heroes cut through cipher after cipher.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n==Production==\n''Sword of Vengeance'' was produced by [[Vertigo Films]] and Red Production, \"which has a long tradition of cooperation with foreign productions\".<ref name=\"FiS2\">{{cite web |title=Filming of the movie Sword of Vengeance completed today in Serbia |url=http://www.filminserbia.com/news/filming-of-the-movie-sword-of-vengeance-completed-today-in-serbia-2/ |website=Film in Serbia |publisher=Film in Serbia Commission |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Vertigo producer Huberta Von Liel noted that except for a few leading actors, the director, and the director of photography, everyone else involved, about 150 cast and crew, were from [[Serbia]].<ref name=\"FiS2\" />\n\n===Background===\nJim Weedon began his career as a film editor, and was encouraged to try directing by [[Ridley Scott]].<ref name=\"Sitges\">{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://sitgesfilmfestival.com/eng/film?id=10003528 |website=[[Sitges Film Festival]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> While ''Sword of Vengeance'' was his first feature film, this was \"after cutting his teeth editing music videos and television commercials.\"<ref name=\"Scheck\" /> He had won awards for his previous work.<ref name=\"Hunter\">{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Allan |title=Sword Of Vengeance |url=https://www.screendaily.com/sword-of-vengeance/5078750.article |website=[[Screen Daily]] |accessdate=20 October 2019 |date=17 October 2014}}</ref> Weedon was approached by Von Liel, who asked if he would be interested in making a period [[revenge]] drama: \"I was incredibly interested in the opportunity but also the fact that Vertigo Films allowed me total creative control visually.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n===Writing and characterisation===\nWhen Julian Unthank joined the project to develop the script, he and Weedon \"stripped back the dialogue to a minimum, something that was used a fair amount in the Spaghetti Westerns.\"<blockquote>We didn't want the film to fall into the standard cinematic tropes, although the script is a basic premise of revenge we wanted the story to unfold in more unexpected prose, especially the ending. I also wanted our hero to be an antihero, rather than the man that saves the day. His character although conflicted tries to atone for his sins but it comes too late, however, his absolution from Anna in the final scene allows him to find peace and solace from his chosen path of revenge.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Design===\nAesthetically, Weedon went for what he called a \"bleach bypass approach\" to [[colour grading|grading]] \"to achieve very little colour in the film.\" Wardrobe was designed to be \"muted,\" working with blues, greys and black; \"the only real colour coming through is the inherent hues from the fur that the heroes wore.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" /> The film's already low colour palette was accentuated by [[principal photography]] taking place in winter, as Jennie Kermode notes; everything appears dark, the sky a \"miserable grey,\" and the land \"hard and unyielding.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite web |last1=Kermode |first1=Jennie |url=https://www.eyeforfilm.co.uk/review/sword-of-vengeance-2015-film-review-by-jennie-kermode |title=''Sword Of Vengeance'' |website=eyeforfilm.co.uk |publisher=Eye For Film (UK) |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Weedon said he wanted the film to \"look and smell of the dark ages.\"<blockquote>Every aspect of the film from locations to clothing had to look worn, beaten and broken. I had shot some commercials in Serbia and found that they had very talented crew in all departments. Milos Djukelic had just co-produced ''Ironclad 2'' so was ahead in terms of the requirements we needed to create this harsh and foreboding world.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\n===Filming and editing===\nLocation scouting took place in July 2013.<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> ''Sword of Vengeance'' was filmed in thirty days in four locations in [[Serbia]].<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> These were the forest of Boj\u010dinska \u0160uma,<ref name=\"FiS\" /> in the [[Progar]] area of [[Belgrade]], as well as the fortress in [[Kalemegdan]], [[Deliblato]] and Pancevo Reva.<ref name=\"FiS2\" /> Weedon said he lost half a [[Stone (unit)|stone]] (seven [[Pound (mass)|pounds]]) the first four weeks into the shooting schedule, which was five to six days a week, in harsh weather, wading through mud every day, and later it snowed: \"days and nights were spent knee deep in mud that at dawn was dangerously frozen ice and by mid morning a muddy mass that was equally harsh.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" /> However, the most difficult part was actually the first two days:<blockquote>Ridiculously we decided to shoot the opening sequence which involved rain fx, horses, stunts, and prosthetics. It was the crew's first two days together, suddenly we are in the rain with actors who can't ride, horses that won't stand still, actors who are going into hyperthermia, and prosthetic limbs that refuse to come apart properly, add in stunts that could only be repeated three to four times, blood that wouldn't squirt sufficiently and the opening crane move into scene that kept breaking down. I did ask myself how the hell did I get into this mess.<ref name=\"Williams\" /></blockquote>\n\nWeedon described the editing of the film with Tom Boulding as \"incredibly fast\".<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n===Sound and music===\nWith so little dialogue in the film, it fell to the [[sound design]]er, Roland Heap, and the composer, [[Stephen Hilton]], to \"convey the unsaid.\" Weedon wanted the audience to have a \"musical roller-coaster ride\": \"Sound is integral to my commercial work and something that always creates the unexpected in the visuals.\"<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\n==Release and reception==\nThe world premiere of ''Sword of Vengeance'' took place at the [[Sitges Film Festival]], where it was in competition, on 10 October 2014.<ref name=\"Sitges\" /> It had its Serbian premiere on 5 March 2015 at the [[FEST (Belgrade)|Belgrade International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |url=http://2015.fest.rs/Movies/1983/Sword-of-Vengeance.shtml |website=2015.fest.rs |publisher=FEST 43rd International Film Festival |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> The British theatrical release did not follow until 29 May.<ref name=\"IMDb\" />\n\n===Home media and streaming===\n''Sword of Vengeance'' has been available on DVD and DVD/Blu-ray (Well Go USA Entertainment,<ref name=\"RT\" /> [[Universal Studios Home Entertainment]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword Of Vengeance [Blu-ray + DVD] |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Sword-Vengeance-Blu-ray-Stanley-Webber/dp/B00V72RPLM |website=[[Amazon.com]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> and streaming services ([[Google Play]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://play.google.com/store/movies/details/Sword_of_Vengeance?gl=no&hl=en&id=TXDQtbnE8ng |website=[[Google Play]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> [[iTunes]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://itunes.apple.com/jo/movie/sword-of-vengeance/id1005046805 |website=[[iTunes]] |publisher=[[Apple, Inc.]] |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref> [[Hulu]])<ref>{{cite web |last1=White |first1=Brett |title=What\u2019s Streaming on Netflix Tonight: \u2018Acts of Vengeance\u2019 + More |url=https://decider.com/2018/01/25/new-on-netflix-acts-of-vengeance/ |website=Decider |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> since May 2015.\n\n===Critical response===\n[[File:Stanley Weber 2018.jpg|thumb|[[Stanley Weber]] in 2018]]\nThe [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] assigns ''Sword of Vengeance'' a rating of 13% based on eight reviews.<ref name=\"RT\">{{cite web |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/sword_of_vengeance |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Critics gave faint to fair praise to the fight scenes, and to [[Stanley Weber]]'s performance, but found the film wanting otherwise, though acknowledging at the same time that the fighting sequences would be enjoyed by action film fans.\n\nAllan Hunter's review following the world premiere at Sitges set the tone for critics into 2015:<blockquote>The only things that appear to be lacking is an original story and some decent dialogue... Stanley Weber's Shadow Walker is very much in the Eastwood tradition down to the squint in his eye and the poncho-like garment draped over his strapping shoulders. He is a man with no name but a remarkably good hair stylist to maintain those immaculate cornrows... The plot is pretty basic but served up with some style by Weedon... His vision of England is bleak, oppressive and uniformly monochrome.  It sometimes seems as if the only colour in the palette of cinematographer August Jakobsson is the crimson of fresh blood. There is a good deal of blood though as limbs are hacked off, throats are slit and eyes plucked out with merry abandon.  Weedon keeps it tight and spare but the real drawbacks are the weary plotting and cheesy dialogue.<ref name=\"Hunter\" /></blockquote>\n\nFrank Scheck, writing for the ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', opines that the title \"pretty much says it all\": there are \"enough clanging sword fights, severed limbs, slit throats and bare-bones dialogue to satisfy genre fans while pretty much failing to provide something of interest to anyone else\"; the film, while \"admirably stylish\", has the feel of an 11th century-set [[video game]]. Stanley Weber stands out among the cast, \"even managing to make such declarations as \"Vengeance is my only belief\" sound convincing.\"<ref name=\"Scheck\" /> Josh Oakley complains that the dialogue is \"overwrought and bland, with the actors apparently instructed to take long pauses between each line\" and \"much of the cast\" seem to have accents like [[Tommy Wiseau]]'s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oakley |first1=Josh |title=\"It is he who brings them hope.\" |url=http://cutprintfilm.com/reviews/sword-of-vengeance/ |website=CutPrintFilm |accessdate=21 October 2019 |date=17 March 2015}}</ref> Ernest Hardy of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' said the fillm \"hits its mark of being a popcorn action flick just fine.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Sword of Vengeance |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/sword-of-vengeance |website=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=21 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nJames Luxford of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' said there is a \"brutal simplicity to the action that will appeal to some,\" but otherwise, ''Sword of Vengeance'' \"seems stretched even for a relatively short film.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Luxford |first1=James |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |journal=[[Radio Times]] |date=May 28, 2015 |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/film/dhgf5q/sword-of-vengeance/ |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref> Jennie Kermode assigned the film 2 stars out of 5, saying the fight scenes were uneven but: \"Weber's work is carefully choreographed and will please fans of fighting films even if it does sometimes take liberties with physics. This is important because there really isn't much else in the film at all.\"<ref name=\"Kermode\" /> Geoffrey Macnab of ''[[The Independent]]'' agreed: \"The ritualised action sequences work well enough. It's just a pity the film-makers did not pay as much attention to the plotting as to the design of the movie.\"<ref name=\"Macnab\">{{cite news|first1=Geoffrey |last1=Macnab |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/sword-of-vengeance-film-review-dialogue-is-sparse-in-this-historical-revenge-drama-10282922.html|title=Sword Of Vengeance, film review: Dialogue is sparse in this historical revenge drama|work=[[The Independent]]|date=28 May 2015|accessdate=2015-11-07}}</ref> Mike McCahill, writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', found the film \"perversely watchable\" and \"modest post-pub fun\"; while it is a \"low-budget\" ''[[Game of Thrones (TV series)|Game of Thrones]]'' \"cash-in\", it at least improves upon its producers' previous effort, the \"risible\" ''[[Hammer of the Gods (2013 film)|Hammer of the Gods]].''<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCahill |first1=Mike |title=Sword of Vengeance review \u2013 perversely watchable Game of Thrones cash-in |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/may/28/sword-of-vengeance-review-game-of-thrones-cash-in |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=28 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nCritics at ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' and ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]]'' characterised the film as a \"daft\" [[slasher film|slasher]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clack |first1=David |title=''Sword of Vengeance'' |journal=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=May 26, 2015 |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/sword-of-vengeance |accessdate=20 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Lea |first1=Andy |title=Review: Sword Of Vengeance (15) is a blunt historical slasher |url=https://www.dailystar.co.uk/movies/review-trailer-sword-vengeance-15-17359254 |accessdate=20 October 2019 |work=[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|The Daily Star]] |date=May 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.metatube.com/en/videos/267263/Sword-of-Vengeance-Official-Trailer-2015/ Official trailer] on MetaTube\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RJQlBW6TTi8 Official trailer] on YouTube\n*{{imdb title|3622332}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|sword_of_vengeance}}\n\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:Serbian films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:British action films]]\n[[Category:Serbian action films]]\n[[Category:British historical films]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 11th century]]\n[[Category:Serbian historical films]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: afficionados->aficionados", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sword_of_Vengeance_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Melita issue", "text_new": "{{multiple image|perrow = 3 |total_width=550\n| image1 = Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange & purple.jpg |width1=643|height1=779\n| image2 = Malta 1922 Melita 1s indigo & sepia.jpg |width2=643|height2=779\n| image3 = Malta 1922 Melita \u00a31 black & carmine-red.jpg |width3=643 |height3=779\n| footer = The different designs used in the Melita issue: [[Penny|pence]] values designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] (left), [[shilling]] values by [[Gianni Vella]] (centre) and [[Pound sterling|pound]] value by Caruana Dingli (right){{efn|There are minor design differences between Caruana Dingli's pence and pound values, including the shape of the value tablet and the typeface used for the country name.}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Melita issue''' is a series of dual-purpose [[Postage stamp|postage]]-and-[[Revenue stamp|revenue stamps]] issued by the [[Crown Colony of Malta]] between 1922 and 1926, depicting the national personification [[Melita (personification)|Melita]]. They were [[commemorative stamp]]s since they celebrated the islands' new status as a [[self-governing colony]] following a new constitution in 1921, but also a [[Definitive stamp|definitive issue]] intended for regular use over an extended period of time.\n\nDesigned by two leading Maltese artists, [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and [[Gianni Vella]], the issue consisted of stamps in various denominations from \u00bc[[pence|d]] to [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]1; Caruana Dingli's designs were used on the pence and pound values and Vella's design on the shilling values. The designs were poorly received when they were issued, and Caruana Dingli himself criticized the execution of the design. In subsequent years, however, Caruana Dingli's design came to be regarded as one of the most iconic Malta stamps, and his design for the figure of Melita formed the basis of the [[Maltese lira]] banknotes of 1989\u20132008 and gold [[bullion coin]]s minted since 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Malta 1899 Melita 2s6d olive-grey.jpg|thumb|left|The 1899 Melita stamp]]\n\nThe oldest known depiction of a personification of Malta dates back to 1481. The figure of [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] seems to have developed from allegorical representations of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between 1530 and 1798.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nMelita first appeared on stamps in 1899. A 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp depicted her holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the Order.<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> This stamp was reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919, and remained in use until it was replaced by the 1922 Melita issue.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013404 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref name=\"mcclellan\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the British [[Crown Colony of Malta]] was granted a limited form of [[self-governing colony|self-government]] according to the Amery-Milner Constitution. This divided control of Malta between two governments: the Maltese Government and the Maltese Imperial Government. The former included a [[Bicameralism|bicameral legislature]] with a [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]], while the Imperial Government was led by the [[List of Governors of Malta|Governor of Malta]], a British colonial official who retained direct responsibility of certain reserved matters such as defence and maintaining public order.<ref name=\"bephila\">{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cassar |first1=Carmel |title=A Concise History of Malta |date=2000 |publisher=Mireva Publications |location=[[Msida]] |isbn=1870579526 |page=204}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 1921, a [[design competition|competition]] was announced calling for the design of a set of stamps to commemorate Malta's partial independence. The stamps were therefore to be [[commemorative stamp|commemoratives]], but they were also intended as [[Definitive stamp|definitives]] for regular use over an extended period of time.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe Maltese wanted to issue the new stamps by the time the new parliament was inaugurated on 1 November 1921. There was not enough time for the stamps to be produced and delivered within that timeframe, however, since the printers [[De La Rue]] had to deal with a large workload, causing delays. The Malta Post Office therefore decided to overprint the then-current definitives (which depicted King [[George V]] and some pictorial scenes, including the 1919 reprint of the 1899 Melita design) with the words \"SELF-GOVERNMENT\" diagonally to commemorate the new constitution.<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The overprinting was carried out by the Government Printing Office in the capital [[Valletta]], and the stamps were released between 12 January and 29 April 1922.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n==Design==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image_style = border:none;\n | image1 = Malta -mix- 2019 by-RaBoe 260.jpg\n | alt1 = A lighthouse\n | image2 = Gozo boat cropped.jpg\n | alt2 = Painting of a boat\n | footer = The St Elmo lighthouse and a [[Gozo boat]] (painting pictured) are depicted in the background of Caruana Dingli's design\n}}\n\nTwo designs were chosen from the competition, one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and one by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design was used for ten denominations: the [[Penny|pence]] values ranging from \u00bcd to 6d, and also the highest value of the set, the [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1. Vella's design was used for the five [[shilling]] values ranging from 1/- to 10/-.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nCaruana Dingli's design depicts [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\"/> The background contains a seascape, with the lighthouse near [[Fort Saint Elmo]] and a [[Gozo boat]] visible. Shields depicting the [[Union Jack]] and a colonial badge representing Malta are located at the bottom of the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nVella's design contains two figures representing Malta and the United Kingdom, Melita and [[Britannia]]. Melita holds an olive branch in her hand, and embraces Britannia by lifting her hand around Britannia's neck. Britannia wears a helmet and holds a shield with the Union Jack. The figure representing the United Kingdom is sometimes interpreted as being a male figure,<ref name=\"bephila\"/><ref name=\"times20111204\">{{cite news |last1=Bonavia |first1=Carmel |title=Stamps marking Malta's constitutional development |url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=4 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911114312/https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref> but was intended as female, with the design representing Malta and Britain as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref name=\"linns\"/><ref name=\"bop1922\"/> This represented the care and protection that Britain offered Malta, and symbolized friendly relations between them. This design also contains the Roman numerals MCMXXI (1921) to the left of the figures. The Maltese emblem is located at the lower left corner, while many small Maltese crosses frame the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange &amp; purple postally and fiscally used.jpg|thumb|300px|Examples of the 1d orange and purple postally used (strip of three with [[Sliema]] postmarks) and fiscally used (single with an [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] cancellation)]]\n\nBoth designs contain the inscription \"POSTAGE [&] REVENUE\", indicating that they were valid for use as both [[postage stamp]]s and [[revenue stamp]]s. They can therefore be found both postally and fiscally used.<ref name=\"mcclellan\">{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n[[File:Watermark crown script CA.jpg|thumb|left|The Multiple Script CA watermark]]\n\nThe stamps of the Melita issue were printed by De La Rue using typography, with the exception of the \u00a31 top value which was [[Intaglio (printmaking)|recess-printed]]. The typographed stamps were printed on chalk-surfaced paper. Each stamp was printed in two operations, with a [[Key type stamp|key plate and a duty plate]]. In most cases each plate was printed in a different colour, but for some of the low values both plates were printed in the same colour.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe [[watermark]] used on the stamps is known as ''Multiple Script CA'', since it consists of the letters \"CA\" (referring to the [[Crown Agents]]) in a script typeface, beneath a representation of the [[Tudor Crown (heraldry)|Tudor crown]], arranged multiple times next to each other. The watermark was sideways for the pence values and upright for the shilling values. The \u00a31 was initially printed with an upright watermark but in 1925 it was also issued with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe pence values were printed in sheets of 160 stamps (consisting of two panes, each containing 8 rows of 10 stamps, separated by a [[Gutter (philately)|gutter]]), the shilling values were printed in sheets of 80 (one pane of 8 rows of 10 stamps) and the \u00a31 value was printed in sheets of 40 (one pane of 4 rows of 10 stamps).<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The stamps were perforated with [[Perforation gauge|gauge]] 14.2 by 14 comb perforations.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nA number of [[Die proof (philately)|die proofs]] and plate proofs of stamps from the Melita issue exist. Die proofs are individual prints from the stamps' original [[Die (philately)|die]]s made at various stages of production, and are impressions of either the key die or the duty die of each value, or composite die proofs of both dies together. Plate proofs, which are test printings made from the stamps' printings plates, exist of the \u00bcd, \u00bdd, 1d, 3d and \u00a31 values in unissued colours. A wide range of versions of these exist, either perforated or imperforate, on unwatermarked or watermarked paper, and with or without a [[Specimen stamp|specimen overprint]]. Specimens of all the stamps in the issued colours also exist, except for the reprints made in slightly different shades, the 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge, and the 1926 postage overprints.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\n==Issued stamps==\n[[File:Malta 1925 Melita 2\u00bdd on 3d bright ultramarine.jpg|thumb|The 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge]]\n\nThe first Melita stamps were issued on 1 August 1922, with the denominations of \u00bdd, 1d, 6d, 1/- and 2/-. A \u00bcd value was issued on 22 August, followed by 2d, 3d, 4d, 2/6, 5/-, 10/- and \u00a31 values on 28 August. A 1\u00bdd value was added on 1 October 1923. On 25 April 1924, the 1d value was reissued in a new colour while the \u00bcd and 3d were reissued in slightly different shades.<ref name=\"jb\">{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=The JB Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop |location=[[Sliema]] |pages=10\u201311 |edition=22}}</ref> The \u00a31 was reissued in a slightly different shade and with a different orientation of the watermark on 14 May 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\nA requirement for a 2\u00bdd value arose when the foreign-letter rate was reduced in 1925;<ref name=\"gps74\">{{cite journal |last1=Poulton |first1=Mark Anthony |title=The Gozo Boat on Malta Stamps |journal=Gozo Philatelic Society Newlsetter |date=2018 |issue=74 |pages=6\u201313 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/handle/123456789/37744}}</ref> stocks of the 3d were overprinted \"Two pence halfpenny\" by the Government Printing Office and were issued on 3 December 1925. A 2\u00bdd value and the 3d in a new colour were subsequently issued on 16 February 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Denomination\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 1\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 2\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" | Paper \n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:8%\" | Watermark orientation\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of issue\n|-\n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-22|22 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | chocolate-brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.50|\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#477159\" | green || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#f67c36\" | orange || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a33550\" | purple || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#894c78\" | bright violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.50|1\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a73422\" | brown-red || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1923-10-01|1 October 1923}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.00|2d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#895732\" | bistre-brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#61beaa\" | turquoise || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-03|3 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-09|9 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4a4742\" | black || bgcolor=\"#e6d649\" | yellow, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|004.00|4d}} || bgcolor=\"#febe2f\" | yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c5b92\" | bright blue || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|006.00|6d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#77743f\" | olive-green || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#5f3364\" | reddish violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|012.00|1/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#26486D\" | indigo || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#78462d\" | sepia || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|024.00|2/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#744028\" | brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c62a1\" | blue || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|030.00|2/6}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#9a427e\" | bright magenta || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#272528\" | black || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|060.00|5/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#c9672a\" | orange-yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#384999\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|120.00|10/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#837873\" | slate-grey || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#7c4d36\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | carmine-red || white, ordinary || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | bright carmine || white, ordinary || sideways || {{sort|1925-05-14|14 May 1925}}\n|- \n|}\n\nSome stamps exist with an inverted watermark, and flaws are known on the 1d and 3d values.<ref name=\"trory\">{{cite book |title=The John A. Trory Specialised Catalogue of Malta |date=1990 |page=20 |edition=6}}</ref>\n\n==1926 Postage overprints==\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 1\u00bdd brown-red.jpg|thumb|The 1\u00bdd with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint]]\n\nDue to a change in procedure, dual-purpose postage-and-revenue stamps were discontinued in 1926 and replaced by separate issues of postage stamps and revenue stamps,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smeed|first1=Graham|title=Malta Revenue Stamps|date=1977|publisher=Malta Study Circle|page=5}}</ref> so it was decided to overprint the stamps of the Melita issue with the word \"POSTAGE\". The [[Forme (printing)|forme]] of the overprint was prepared by John Muscat Fenech and Carmelo Cacopardo, and the overprinting was hastily carried out by the Government Printing Office on a Warfedale printing press in the last week of March 1926. The ink used in the overprinting was a special mix made at the Office of Public Health.<ref name=\"invert\"/> The overprinting was applied to all the stamps from \u00bcd to 10/-, except those which had been earlier replaced by new colours, and the stamps were issued on 1 April 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The overprints were on sale for only about a week, and a new series of stamps bearing the \"POSTAGE\" inscription was issued only five days later on 6 April.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref name=\"gsm2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Davenhill |first1=Noel |title=British Colonial and Protectorate Stamps \u2013 Part 19: Malta |magazine=[[Gibbons Stamp Monthly]] |date=December 2019 |volume=50 |issue=7 |pages=62\u201368 |publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd}}</ref>\n\nSome stamps with had errors were detected during the printing, and these were kept by the Acting Postmaster General before being burnt at the Power Station. Despite this, some stamps with errors still ended up in circulation, including the 3d value with the overprint inverted, and various denominations with the overprints misplaced to varying degrees, the most notable being a variety of the 4d in which the overprint reads \"AGE POST\".<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\n===3d with inverted overprint===\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 3d black on yellow overprint inverted.jpg|thumb|The 3d with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint inverted]]\n\nThe 3d black on yellow is known with the [[Invert error|overprint inverted]], and it is one of Malta's best-known error stamps. It is believed that only two sheets of the error were printed, and they were allegedly acquired on the first day of issue by Alfredo Caruana Gatto, a [[Maltese Political Union]] politician who was a member of the Senate and who had been Minister for Justice in 1921\u201322. The exact circumstances of their issue remain unclear, and it is not known whether they were acquired over the Post Office counter or not. Caruana Gatto is said to have immediately sold the two sheets to Carol Saliba and Pio Grech, and the sheets were eventually broken down and sold to stamp dealers and collectors. A small amount of the error stamps were used on mail by philatelists, but the vast majority were retained in [[Mint stamp|mint condition]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nIn 1930, uncertainty about the stamp's issue formed the basis of a political campaign by the [[Constitutional Party (Malta)|Constitutional Party]] against the [[Nationalist Party (Malta)|Nationalist Party]] which became known as the \"Postage Stamps Scandal\". The matter was brought up in the Legislative Assembly on 31 March 1930 when Constitutional Party member Alfred Gera De Petri asked Robert Hamilton, the Minister for Posts, about the circumstances of the stamp's issue. A committee was later appointed to investigate the matter, and it included [[Gerald Strickland, 1st Baron Strickland|Gerald Strickland]], Hamilton, Walter Salomone, [[Paul Boffa]] and [[Ugo Pasquale Mifsud]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nThe committee members belonging to the Constitutional Party produced a report in which they stated that there was no evidence that the error was ever sold at a Post Office or that Caruana Gatto (who had died in 1926) had sold the stamps. They concluded that the inverted overprint was applied at the Government Printing Office without authorisation to sheets of genuine stamps which were not part of the Post Office stock, meaning that the overprints were forged. Boffa mentioned that the overprinting might have even been done outside the Government Printing Office, while Mifsud only agreed with the conclusion that there was no evidence of Caruana Gatto's involvement in the matter. There were gaps in the evidence collected by the committee, and it did not produce any arguments which countered various opinions that the overprints were the result of a genuine mistake, making its findings inconclusive. The committee's report was criticized in the press.<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nPhilatelists regard the inverted overprint as a genuine error,<ref name=\"sg\"/> even though its exact origins remain unknown.<ref name=\"invert\">{{cite journal |last1=Ganado |first1=Albert |title=The Melita 3d. Postage Inverted: Politics embroil philately |journal=Melita Historica |date=2007 |volume=XIV |issue=4 |pages=409\u2013428 |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf |issn=1021-6952|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121232400/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe stamps received mostly negative reactions from the public and stamp collectors upon their release. Even Caruana Dingli was dissatisfied with the way the stamps were printed, stating in the local newspaper ''Il Popolo di Malta'' on 4 August 1922 that:<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n{{cquote|After correcting the first proofs and suggesting certain artistic retouching, I regret to say, that the result still fell short of my expectations. My original was copied by hand and alterations were introduced resulting in a totally different effect from that originally intended.|20px}}\nAmongst other criticism, he expressed his dissatisfaction that the lighthouse in the background was remodelled to look like a [[beehive]] or the [[Rotunda of Mosta|Mosta Dome]]. He also complained that the colours were not to his liking, and that he had not been consulted about them. He exhibited an enlarged version of his original design at the [[National Library of Malta|Bibliotheca]] in Valletta to showcase the difference in the designs.<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 4d yellow &amp; bright blue.jpg|thumb|left|The colour scheme of the 4d was criticized when the stamps were issued]]\n\nAn article in ''[[The Boy's Own Paper]]'' described the issue as a \"handsome set\", but also mentioned the criticism aimed at the colour scheme of the 4d value in yellow and blue. This article incorrectly identified Melita as being a [[Nereid|sea nymph]].<ref name=\"bop1922\">{{cite book |title=The Boy's Own Paper |date=1922 |publisher=Leisure Hour Office |pages=227\u2013228 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsPnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q&f=false |volume=45 |chapter=The \"B.O.P.\" Stamp Corner}}</ref> In ''Mekeel's Weekly Stamp News'' of 16 May 1927, a certain Capt. H. W. Jessop wrote that:<ref name=\"linns\">{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{cquote|though not in themselves displeasing, [the stamps] did not meet with a very enthusiastic reception either from the general public or from collectors.|20px}}\nCriticism was also directed towards the lack of a portrait of King [[George V]] on the stamps, although the stamps were aimed at specifically manifesting Malta's newly established freedom from total British control.<ref name=\"linns\"/>\n\nThe 1926 Postage overprints were widely criticized as being unnecessary,<ref name=\"gsm2019\"/> and they were unpopular both locally and among collectors.<ref name=\"gps74\"/>\n\nIn contrast to when it was issued, today Caruana Dingli's design is held in high esteem, and in 2011 [[MaltaPost]] stated that \"it is widely considered to be one of Malta's most beautiful stamps.\"<ref name=\"maltapost2011\"/> A 2019 article in the ''Stamp Magazine'' describes the Melita issue as \"some of Malta's finest\" stamp designs, but also comments on the contrast between Caruana Dingli's and Vella's Melitas, describing the latter as having \"an awkward pose\".<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Winchester |first1=John |title=The odd couple |magazine=Stamp Magazine |date=February 2019 |volume=85 |issue=2 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n==Sale and collecting==\nIn 1922\u201323 the Post Office recorded an increase of \u00a31920. 19s. 9\u00bdd. in revenue when compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153623/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> This increase was attributed to the sale of stamps to [[philately|philatelists]] \"owing to the issue of new design stamps\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1924 |date=1925 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108154434/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1922 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1922 to 31 March 1923.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153618/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new stamps issued during this period were a \u00bcd surcharged stamp on 15 April, 6d and \u00bdd Self-Government overprints on 19 and 24 April respectively, and the Melita issue between 1 and 28 August. The Melita issue was the only issue with a new design.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} A massive increase of \u00a327977. 16s. 6\u00bdd.  in Post Office revenue was registered in 1925\u201326 when compared to 1924\u201325, and this was attributed to \"an abnormal quantity of stamps sold to collectors for philatelic purposes\" along with increased use of stamps for postal purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155457/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1926 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1925 to 31 March 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155453/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new postage stamps issued during this period were all from the Melita issue: the reprint of the \u00a31 on 14 May 1925, the 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge in December 1925, and the 2\u00bdd and 3d in new colours on 16 February 1926. In addition, there were two new sets of [[postage due]] stamps issued on 16 April and 20 July 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} In 1926\u201327, another massive increase of \u00a324870. 8s. 2d. was attributed to \"large sales of stamps overprinted \"Postage\".\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1927 |date=1928 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108160038/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>\n\nDue to the criticism at the colour scheme of the 4d value, that stamp was reportedly withdrawn by the postal authorities soon after it was issued. Some believed that the stamp could become a rarity and examples of it were sold for as much as 30/-. After a couple of days the stamp once again became available at post offices,<ref name=\"bop1922\"/> and it is no longer scarcer than the other stamps in the issue.<ref name=\"sg\"/> Today, the 1922\u201326 stamps are not rare, and the lower values up to the 2/6 are relatively cheap. The higher values are more expensive,<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\"/> with the most valuable stamp being the original \u00a31 value of 1922 with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1930 AR cover to United States.jpg|thumb|1\u00bdd and 3d Melita stamps with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint used on a 1930 [[Avis de r\u00e9ception|AR]] registered cover to the United States. The cover was sent by Rupert Forbes-Bentley, a stamp dealer.<ref name=\"invert\"/>]]\n\nAlthough the 1926 Postage overprints were only on sale for about one week, the bulk of the stamps were sold to stamp dealers and collectors so most of them remain common. However, some values sold out soon after they were issued<ref name=\"gps74\"/> and stamps with the denominations of 4d, 2/-, 2/6 and 5/- are quite expensive today. Since they were only in use briefly, most of the 1926 overprints are more valuable in used condition.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The \"POSTAGE\" overprint has also been [[Philatelic fakes and forgeries|forged]], particularly on the 2/- and 2/6 denominations and on the 3d with inverted overprint.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\nThe Malta Study Circle, a group of philatelists who study Malta's stamps and postal history, has produced a number of publications relating to the Melita issue. Two study papers which related to the original 1922\u201326 issue and the 1926 Postage overprints were published in 1970,<ref>{{cite web |title=Melita 1922\u20131926 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112251/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and they were combined into a single paper in 1972. A rewritten paper was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Study Papers |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112254/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The Study Circle's newsletter which is published three times a year is also entitled ''Melita''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112257/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe first set of post-independence Malta definitive stamps, which was issued on 7 January 1965, included an allegorical representation of Melita on the 2/6 denomination which commemorated the [[State of Malta]]. The design by [[Emvin Cremona]] depicts Melita holding a spear and a shield with Malta's 1943\u201364 coat of arms (including the [[George Cross]]), and she is shown sitting among ruins as if after a battle.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Casingena |first1=Mario |title=Melita |journal=The Melite Post |date=March 2018 |issue=6 |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/32002/1/The%20Melite%20Post%20-%20Issue%206.pdf |publisher=\u017bejtun Philatelic Society |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200418135622/https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/32002/1/The%20Melite%20Post%20-%20Issue%206.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn allegorical figure with a pose similar to Caruana Dingli's Melita design was used on the fifth and final series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes. These banknotes were introduced by the [[Central Bank of Malta]] on 18 September 1989, coinciding with the 25th anniversary of independence, and they had four denominations: Lm2, Lm5, Lm10 and Lm20. Another series of banknotes with the same design but with amended security features was issued on 1 June 1994. Versions with signatures of different Governors of the Central Bank were issued in 1997, 1999 and 2001, and there was also a special issue for collectors in 2000.<ref>{{cite book |title=Said Malta Coin & Banknote Catalogue 2010 |date=2010 |publisher=Said International Ltd |pages=180\u2013193}}</ref> These banknotes remained in use until Malta adopted the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, and remained legal tender until 31 January 2008; they were demonetized ten years later on 31 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2011, MaltaPost issued a [[miniature sheet]] containing a \u20ac4.16 stamp to commemorate the 90th anniversary of the establishment of Malta's [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]]. This issue depicted the \u00a31 Melita stamp of 1922 as a [[stamp on stamp]].<ref name=\"maltapost2011\">{{cite news|title=Commemorative Stamp Issue \u2013 90th Anniversary of the Malta Senate and Legislative Assembly|url=https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025224/https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archivedate=16 March 2017|publisher=[[MaltaPost]]|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCaruana Dingli's Melita design was reused for the [[Melita bullion coins]], a series of gold [[bullion coin]]s minted by the Central Bank of Malta in collaboration with [[Lombard Bank]]. The coins were minted in three sizes and denominations (\u20ac25, \u20ac50 and \u20ac100), and were first issued on 30 November 2018. There are plans to mint coins according to demand, retaining the same design except for the year of minting.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Melita 1922\u201326 \u2013 Study Paper 24 |date=1972 |publisher=Malta Study Circle}}\n*{{cite magazine |last1=Pogson |first1=L. V. |title=Malta. 1922. \u00a31. |journal=Melita |volume=1 |issue=1 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |publisher=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415130044/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Melita issue}}\n\n[[Category:Postage stamps]]\n[[Category:Commemorative stamps]]\n[[Category:Philately of Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 works]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image|perrow = 3 |total_width=550\n| image1 = Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange & purple.jpg |width1=643|height1=779\n| image2 = Malta 1922 Melita 1s indigo & sepia.jpg |width2=643|height2=779\n| image3 = Malta 1922 Melita \u00a31 black & carmine-red.jpg |width3=643 |height3=779\n| footer = The different designs used in the Melita issue: [[Penny|pence]] values designed by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] (left), [[shilling]] values by [[Gianni Vella]] (centre) and [[Pound sterling|pound]] value by Caruana Dingli (right){{efn|There are minor design differences between Caruana Dingli's pence and pound values, including the shape of the value tablet and the typeface used for the country name.}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Melita issue''' is a series of dual-purpose [[Postage stamp|postage]]-and-[[Revenue stamp|revenue stamps]] issued by the [[Crown Colony of Malta]] between 1922 and 1926, depicting the national personification [[Melita (personification)|Melita]]. They were [[commemorative stamp]]s since they celebrated the islands' new status as a [[self-governing colony]] following a new constitution in 1921, but also a [[Definitive stamp|definitive issue]] intended for regular use over an extended period of time.\n\nDesigned by two leading Maltese artists, [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and [[Gianni Vella]], the issue consisted of stamps in various denominations from \u00bc[[pence|d]] to [[\u00a3sd|\u00a3]]1; Caruana Dingli's designs were used on the pence and pound values and Vella's design on the shilling values. The designs were poorly received when they were issued, and Caruana Dingli himself criticized the execution of the design. In subsequent years, however, Caruana Dingli's design came to be regarded as one of the most iconic Malta stamps, and his design for the figure of Melita formed the basis of the [[Maltese lira]] banknotes of 1989\u20132008 and gold [[bullion coin]]s minted since 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Malta 1899 Melita 2s6d olive-grey.jpg|thumb|left|The 1899 Melita stamp]]\n\nThe oldest known depiction of a personification of Malta dates back to 1481. The figure of [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] seems to have developed from allegorical representations of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St John]], which [[History of Malta under the Order of Saint John|ruled Malta]] between 1530 and 1798.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kinnane-Roelofsma |first1=Derk |title=Britannia and Melita: Pseudomorphic Sisters |journal=Journal of the Warbourg and Courtauld Insitute |date=1996 |volume=59 |pages=130\u2013147}}</ref>\n\nMelita first appeared on stamps in 1899. A 2[[shilling|s]]/6d olive-grey stamp depicted her holding a sword and a shield, the latter emblazoned with the [[Maltese cross]]. In the background were the flags of Malta and of the Order.<ref>{{cite web |title=The \"Melita\" Stamp of Malta |url=https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |website=Mintage World |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122142635/https://www.mintageworld.com/media/detail/7401-the-melita-stamp-of-malta/ |archivedate=22 January 2019 |date=21 August 2018}}</ref> This stamp was reissued with a different [[watermark]] in 1919, and remained in use until it was replaced by the 1922 Melita issue.<ref name=\"sg\">{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Stamp Catalogue: Commonwealth and British Empire Stamps 1840\u20131970 |date=2015 |publisher=[[Stanley Gibbons]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-85259-918-1 |pages=401\u2013404 |edition=117}}</ref> Special printings of the 1899 design, sometimes in new colours or watermarks, were also issued with [[overprint]]s for [[Revenue stamps of Malta|revenue purposes]] between 1902 and 1908.<ref name=\"mcclellan\"/>\n\nIn 1921, the British [[Crown Colony of Malta]] was granted a limited form of [[self-governing colony|self-government]] according to the Amery-Milner Constitution. This divided control of Malta between two governments: the Maltese Government and the Maltese Imperial Government. The former included a [[Bicameralism|bicameral legislature]] with a [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]], while the Imperial Government was led by the [[List of Governors of Malta|Governor of Malta]], a British colonial official who retained direct responsibility of certain reserved matters such as defence and maintaining public order.<ref name=\"bephila\">{{cite web|title=Melita Issue of Malta Stamps: 1922\u201326|url=http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|website=British Empire Philately|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316113650/http://www.bephila.com/articles/melita-issue-of-malta-stamps-1922-26|archivedate=16 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cassar |first1=Carmel |title=A Concise History of Malta |date=2000 |publisher=Mireva Publications |location=[[Msida]] |isbn=1870579526 |page=204}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 June 1921, a [[design competition|competition]] was announced calling for the design of a set of stamps to commemorate Malta's partial independence. The stamps were therefore to be [[commemorative stamp|commemoratives]], but they were also intended as [[Definitive stamp|definitives]] for regular use over an extended period of time.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe Maltese wanted to issue the new stamps by the time the new parliament was inaugurated on 1 November 1921. There was not enough time for the stamps to be produced and delivered within that timeframe, however, since the printers [[De La Rue]] had to deal with a large workload, causing delays. The Malta Post Office therefore decided to overprint the then-current definitives (which depicted King [[George V]] and some pictorial scenes, including the 1919 reprint of the 1899 Melita design) with the words \"SELF-GOVERNMENT\" diagonally to commemorate the new constitution.<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The overprinting was carried out by the Government Printing Office in the capital [[Valletta]], and the stamps were released between 12 January and 29 April 1922.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n==Design==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 320\n | image_style = border:none;\n | image1 = Malta -mix- 2019 by-RaBoe 260.jpg\n | alt1 = A lighthouse\n | image2 = Gozo boat cropped.jpg\n | alt2 = Painting of a boat\n | footer = The St Elmo lighthouse and a [[Gozo boat]] (painting pictured) are depicted in the background of Caruana Dingli's design\n}}\n\nTwo designs were chosen from the competition, one by [[Edward Caruana Dingli (artist)|Edward Caruana Dingli]] and one by [[Gianni Vella]]. Caruana Dingli's design was used for ten denominations: the [[Penny|pence]] values ranging from \u00bcd to 6d, and also the highest value of the set, the [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1. Vella's design was used for the five [[shilling]] values ranging from 1/- to 10/-.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nCaruana Dingli's design depicts [[Melita (personification)|Melita]] as a robed and helmeted figure holding a [[rudder]], representing Malta as being in control of her own destiny.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\"/> The background contains a seascape, with the lighthouse near [[Fort Saint Elmo]] and a [[Gozo boat]] visible. Shields depicting the [[Union Jack]] and a colonial badge representing Malta are located at the bottom of the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nVella's design contains two figures representing Malta and the United Kingdom, Melita and [[Britannia]]. Melita holds an olive branch in her hand, and embraces Britannia by lifting her hand around Britannia's neck. Britannia wears a helmet and holds a shield with the Union Jack. The figure representing the United Kingdom is sometimes interpreted as being a male figure,<ref name=\"bephila\"/><ref name=\"times20111204\">{{cite news |last1=Bonavia |first1=Carmel |title=Stamps marking Malta's constitutional development |url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=4 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911114312/https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20111204/life-features/Stamps-marking-Malta-s-constitutional-development.397019 |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref> but was intended as female, with the design representing Malta and Britain as sisters or mother and daughter.<ref name=\"linns\"/><ref name=\"bop1922\"/> This represented the care and protection that Britain offered Malta, and symbolized friendly relations between them. This design also contains the Roman numerals MCMXXI (1921) to the left of the figures. The Maltese emblem is located at the lower left corner, while many small Maltese crosses frame the design.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 1d orange &amp; purple postally and fiscally used.jpg|thumb|300px|Examples of the 1d orange and purple postally used (strip of three with [[Sliema]] postmarks) and fiscally used (single with an [[Anglo-Egyptian Bank]] cancellation)]]\n\nBoth designs contain the inscription \"POSTAGE [&] REVENUE\", indicating that they were valid for use as both [[postage stamp]]s and [[revenue stamp]]s. They can therefore be found both postally and fiscally used.<ref name=\"mcclellan\">{{cite web|last1=McClellan|first1=Andrew|title=Malta|url=http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|website=Revenue Reverend|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170924105952/http://www.revrevd.com/malta.html|archivedate=24 September 2017|date=2011\u201317}}</ref>\n\n==Technical details==\n[[File:Watermark crown script CA.jpg|thumb|left|The Multiple Script CA watermark]]\n\nThe stamps of the Melita issue were printed by De La Rue using typography, with the exception of the \u00a31 top value which was [[Intaglio (printmaking)|recess-printed]]. The typographed stamps were printed on chalk-surfaced paper. Each stamp was printed in two operations, with a [[Key type stamp|key plate and a duty plate]]. In most cases each plate was printed in a different colour, but for some of the low values both plates were printed in the same colour.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe [[watermark]] used on the stamps is known as ''Multiple Script CA'', since it consists of the letters \"CA\" (referring to the [[Crown Agents]]) in a script typeface, beneath a representation of the [[Tudor Crown (heraldry)|Tudor crown]], arranged multiple times next to each other. The watermark was sideways for the pence values and upright for the shilling values. The \u00a31 was initially printed with an upright watermark but in 1925 it was also issued with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nThe pence values were printed in sheets of 160 stamps (consisting of two panes, each containing 8 rows of 10 stamps, separated by a [[Gutter (philately)|gutter]]), the shilling values were printed in sheets of 80 (one pane of 8 rows of 10 stamps) and the \u00a31 value was printed in sheets of 40 (one pane of 4 rows of 10 stamps).<ref name=\"bephila\"/> The stamps were perforated with [[Perforation gauge|gauge]] 14.2 by 14 comb perforations.<ref name=\"bephila\"/>\n\nA number of [[Die proof (philately)|die proofs]] and plate proofs of stamps from the Melita issue exist. Die proofs are individual prints from the stamps' original [[Die (philately)|die]]s made at various stages of production, and are impressions of either the key die or the duty die of each value, or composite die proofs of both dies together. Plate proofs, which are test printings made from the stamps' printings plates, exist of the \u00bcd, \u00bdd, 1d, 3d and \u00a31 values in unissued colours. A wide range of versions of these exist, either perforated or imperforate, on unwatermarked or watermarked paper, and with or without a [[Specimen stamp|specimen overprint]]. Specimens of all the stamps in the issued colours also exist, except for the reprints made in slightly different shades, the 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge, and the 1926 postage overprints.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\n==Issued stamps==\n[[File:Malta 1925 Melita 2\u00bdd on 3d bright ultramarine.jpg|thumb|The 1925 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge]]\n\nThe first Melita stamps were issued on 1 August 1922, with the denominations of \u00bdd, 1d, 6d, 1/- and 2/-. A \u00bcd value was issued on 22 August, followed by 2d, 3d, 4d, 2/6, 5/-, 10/- and \u00a31 values on 28 August. A 1\u00bdd value was added on 1 October 1923. On 25 April 1924, the 1d value was reissued in a new colour while the \u00bcd and 3d were reissued in slightly different shades.<ref name=\"jb\">{{cite book |last1=Buttigieg |first1=Joseph |title=The JB Catalogue of Malta Stamps and Postal History |date=2014 |publisher=Sliema Stamp Shop |location=[[Sliema]] |pages=10\u201311 |edition=22}}</ref> The \u00a31 was reissued in a slightly different shade and with a different orientation of the watermark on 14 May 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\nA requirement for a 2\u00bdd value arose when the foreign-letter rate was reduced in 1925;<ref name=\"gps74\">{{cite journal |last1=Poulton |first1=Mark Anthony |title=The Gozo Boat on Malta Stamps |journal=Gozo Philatelic Society Newlsetter |date=2018 |issue=74 |pages=6\u201313 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/handle/123456789/37744}}</ref> stocks of the 3d were overprinted \"Two pence halfpenny\" by the Government Printing Office and were issued on 3 December 1925. A 2\u00bdd value and the 3d in a new colour were subsequently issued on 16 February 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Denomination\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 1\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:18%\" | Colour 2\n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" | Paper \n! class=\"unsortable\" scope=\"col\" style =\"width:8%\" | Watermark orientation\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of issue\n|-\n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-22|22 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.25|\u00bcd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#773b31\" | chocolate-brown || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|000.50|\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#477159\" | green || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#f67c36\" | orange || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a33550\" | purple || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.00|1d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#894c78\" | bright violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|001.50|1\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#a73422\" | brown-red || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1923-10-01|1 October 1923}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.00|2d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#895732\" | bistre-brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#61beaa\" | turquoise || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-03|3 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd on 3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1925-12-09|9 December 1925}}\n|- \n| {{sort|002.50|2\u00bdd}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#606fa8\" | cobalt || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#476eb9\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1924-04-25|25 April 1924}}\n|- \n| {{sort|003.00|3d}} || colspan=2 style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4a4742\" | black || bgcolor=\"#e6d649\" | yellow, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1926-02-16|16 February 1926}}\n|- \n| {{sort|004.00|4d}} || bgcolor=\"#febe2f\" | yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c5b92\" | bright blue || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|006.00|6d}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#77743f\" | olive-green || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#5f3364\" | reddish violet || white, chalk-surfaced || sideways || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|012.00|1/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#26486D\" | indigo || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#78462d\" | sepia || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|024.00|2/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#744028\" | brown || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#4c62a1\" | blue || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-01|1 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|030.00|2/6}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#9a427e\" | bright magenta || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#272528\" | black || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|060.00|5/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#c9672a\" | orange-yellow || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#384999\" | bright ultramarine || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|120.00|10/-}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#837873\" | slate-grey || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#7c4d36\" | brown || white, chalk-surfaced || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | carmine-red || white, ordinary || upright || {{sort|1922-08-28|28 August 1922}}\n|- \n| {{sort|240.00|\u00a31}} || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#211f22\" | black || style=\"color:#ffffff\" bgcolor=\"#b32026\" | bright carmine || white, ordinary || sideways || {{sort|1925-05-14|14 May 1925}}\n|- \n|}\n\nSome stamps exist with an inverted watermark, and flaws are known on the 1d and 3d values.<ref name=\"trory\">{{cite book |title=The John A. Trory Specialised Catalogue of Malta |date=1990 |page=20 |edition=6}}</ref>\n\n==1926 Postage overprints==\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 1\u00bdd brown-red.jpg|thumb|The 1\u00bdd with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint]]\n\nDue to a change in procedure, dual-purpose postage-and-revenue stamps were discontinued in 1926 and replaced by separate issues of postage stamps and revenue stamps,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Smeed|first1=Graham|title=Malta Revenue Stamps|date=1977|publisher=Malta Study Circle|page=5}}</ref> so it was decided to overprint the stamps of the Melita issue with the word \"POSTAGE\". The [[Forme (printing)|forme]] of the overprint was prepared by John Muscat Fenech and Carmelo Cacopardo, and the overprinting was hastily carried out by the Government Printing Office on a Warfedale printing press in the last week of March 1926. The ink used in the overprinting was a special mix made at the Office of Public Health.<ref name=\"invert\"/> The overprinting was applied to all the stamps from \u00bcd to 10/-, except those which had been earlier replaced by new colours, and the stamps were issued on 1 April 1926.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The overprints were on sale for only about a week, and a new series of stamps bearing the \"POSTAGE\" inscription was issued only five days later on 6 April.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref name=\"gsm2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Davenhill |first1=Noel |title=British Colonial and Protectorate Stamps \u2013 Part 19: Malta |magazine=[[Gibbons Stamp Monthly]] |date=December 2019 |volume=50 |issue=7 |pages=62\u201368 |publisher=Stanley Gibbons Ltd}}</ref>\n\nSome stamps with had errors were detected during the printing, and these were kept by the Acting Postmaster General before being burnt at the Power Station. Despite this, some stamps with errors still ended up in circulation, including the 3d value with the overprint inverted, and various denominations with the overprints misplaced to varying degrees, the most notable being a variety of the 4d in which the overprint reads \"AGE POST\".<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\n===3d with inverted overprint===\n[[File:Malta 1926 Melita Postage 3d black on yellow overprint inverted.jpg|thumb|The 3d with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint inverted]]\n\nThe 3d black on yellow is known with the [[Invert error|overprint inverted]], and it is one of Malta's best-known error stamps. It is believed that only two sheets of the error were printed, and they were allegedly acquired on the first day of issue by Alfredo Caruana Gatto, a [[Maltese Political Union]] politician who was a member of the Senate and who had been Minister for Justice in 1921\u201322. The exact circumstances of their issue remain unclear, and it is not known whether they were acquired over the Post Office counter or not. Caruana Gatto is said to have immediately sold the two sheets to Carol Saliba and Pio Grech, and the sheets were eventually broken down and sold to stamp dealers and collectors. A small amount of the error stamps were used on mail by philatelists, but the vast majority were retained in [[Mint stamp|mint condition]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nIn 1930, uncertainty about the stamp's issue formed the basis of a political campaign by the [[Constitutional Party (Malta)|Constitutional Party]] against the [[Nationalist Party (Malta)|Nationalist Party]] which became known as the \"Postage Stamps Scandal\". The matter was brought up in the Legislative Assembly on 31 March 1930 when Constitutional Party member Alfred Gera De Petri asked Robert Hamilton, the Minister for Posts, about the circumstances of the stamp's issue. A committee was later appointed to investigate the matter, and it included [[Gerald Strickland, 1st Baron Strickland|Gerald Strickland]], Hamilton, Walter Salomone, [[Paul Boffa]] and [[Ugo Pasquale Mifsud]].<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nThe committee members belonging to the Constitutional Party produced a report in which they stated that there was no evidence that the error was ever sold at a Post Office or that Caruana Gatto (who had died in 1926) had sold the stamps. They concluded that the inverted overprint was applied at the Government Printing Office without authorisation to sheets of genuine stamps which were not part of the Post Office stock, meaning that the overprints were forged. Boffa mentioned that the overprinting might have even been done outside the Government Printing Office, while Mifsud only agreed with the conclusion that there was no evidence of Caruana Gatto's involvement in the matter. There were gaps in the evidence collected by the committee, and it did not produce any arguments which countered various opinions that the overprints were the result of a genuine mistake, making its findings inconclusive. The committee's report was criticized in the press.<ref name=\"invert\"/>\n\nPhilatelists regard the inverted overprint as a genuine error,<ref name=\"sg\"/> even though its exact origins remain unknown.<ref name=\"invert\">{{cite journal |last1=Ganado |first1=Albert |title=The Melita 3d. Postage Inverted: Politics embroil philately |journal=Melita Historica |date=2007 |volume=XIV |issue=4 |pages=409\u2013428 |url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf |issn=1021-6952|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121232400/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Melita%20Historica/MH.14(2004-07)/MH.14(2007)4/04.pdf|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe stamps received mostly negative reactions from the public and stamp collectors upon their release. Even Caruana Dingli was dissatisfied with the way the stamps were printed, stating in the local newspaper ''Il Popolo di Malta'' on 4 August 1922 that:<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n{{cquote|After correcting the first proofs and suggesting certain artistic retouching, I regret to say, that the result still fell short of my expectations. My original was copied by hand and alterations were introduced resulting in a totally different effect from that originally intended.|20px}}\nAmongst other criticism, he expressed his dissatisfaction that the lighthouse in the background was remodelled to look like a [[beehive]] or the [[Rotunda of Mosta|Mosta Dome]]. He also complained that the colours were not to his liking, and that he had not been consulted about them. He exhibited an enlarged version of his original design at the [[National Library of Malta|Bibliotheca]] in Valletta to showcase the difference in the designs.<ref name=\"times20111204\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1922 Melita 4d yellow &amp; bright blue.jpg|thumb|left|The colour scheme of the 4d was criticized when the stamps were issued]]\n\nAn article in ''[[The Boy's Own Paper]]'' described the issue as a \"handsome set\", but also mentioned the criticism aimed at the colour scheme of the 4d value in yellow and blue. This article incorrectly identified Melita as being a [[Nereid|sea nymph]].<ref name=\"bop1922\">{{cite book |title=The Boy's Own Paper |date=1922 |publisher=Leisure Hour Office |pages=227\u2013228 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IsPnAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA227#v=onepage&q&f=false |volume=45 |chapter=The \"B.O.P.\" Stamp Corner}}</ref> In ''Mekeel's Weekly Stamp News'' of 16 May 1927, a certain Capt. H. W. Jessop wrote that:<ref name=\"linns\">{{cite web |title=Malta's 1922 Melita issue: Fine art or poorly done stamps? |url=https://www.linns.com/news/us-stamps-postal-history/2017/january/malta-melita-stamp-issue-fine-art-poorly-done.html |website=[[Linn's Stamp News]] |date=1 January 2017|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/75cWftBrr|archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n{{cquote|though not in themselves displeasing, [the stamps] did not meet with a very enthusiastic reception either from the general public or from collectors.|20px}}\nCriticism was also directed towards the lack of a portrait of King [[George V]] on the stamps, although the stamps were aimed at specifically manifesting Malta's newly established freedom from total British control.<ref name=\"linns\"/>\n\nThe 1926 Postage overprints were widely criticized as being unnecessary,<ref name=\"gsm2019\"/> and they were unpopular both locally and among collectors.<ref name=\"gps74\"/>\n\nIn contrast to when it was issued, today Caruana Dingli's design is held in high esteem, and in 2011 [[MaltaPost]] stated that \"it is widely considered to be one of Malta's most beautiful stamps.\"<ref name=\"maltapost2011\"/> A 2019 article in the ''Stamp Magazine'' describes the Melita issue as \"some of Malta's finest\" stamp designs, but also comments on the contrast between Caruana Dingli's and Vella's Melitas, describing the latter as having \"an awkward pose\".<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Winchester |first1=John |title=The odd couple |magazine=Stamp Magazine |date=February 2019 |volume=85 |issue=2 |page=51}}</ref>\n\n==Sale and collecting==\nIn 1922\u201323 the Post Office recorded an increase of \u00a31920. 19s. 9\u00bdd. in revenue when compared to the previous year.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153623/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> This increase was attributed to the sale of stamps to [[philately|philatelists]] \"owing to the issue of new design stamps\".<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1924 |date=1925 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108154434/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1924/1924_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1922 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1922 to 31 March 1923.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1922 |date=1923 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108153618/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1922/1922_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new stamps issued during this period were a \u00bcd surcharged stamp on 15 April, 6d and \u00bdd Self-Government overprints on 19 and 24 April respectively, and the Melita issue between 1 and 28 August. The Melita issue was the only issue with a new design.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} A massive increase of \u00a327977. 16s. 6\u00bdd.  in Post Office revenue was registered in 1925\u201326 when compared to 1924\u201325, and this was attributed to \"an abnormal quantity of stamps sold to collectors for philatelic purposes\" along with increased use of stamps for postal purposes.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155457/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>{{efn|The statistics in the 1926 Blue Book are for the period lasting from 1 April 1925 to 31 March 1926.<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1926 |date=1927 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108155453/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1926/1926_section2.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Abstract of the Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref> The only new postage stamps issued during this period were all from the Melita issue: the reprint of the \u00a31 on 14 May 1925, the 2\u00bdd on 3d surcharge in December 1925, and the 2\u00bdd and 3d in new colours on 16 February 1926. In addition, there were two new sets of [[postage due]] stamps issued on 16 April and 20 July 1925.<ref name=\"sg\"/>}} In 1926\u201327, another massive increase of \u00a324870. 8s. 2d. was attributed to \"large sales of stamps overprinted \"Postage\".\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Malta Blue Book for the Year 1927 |date=1928 |publisher=Government Printing Office |url=https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20180108160038/https://nso.gov.mt/en/nso/Historical_Statistics/Malta_Blue_Books/Documents/1927/1927_section3.pdf |archivedate=8 January 2018 |chapter=Comparative Yearly Statements of Revenue and Expenditure}}</ref>\n\nDue to the criticism at the colour scheme of the 4d value, that stamp was reportedly withdrawn by the postal authorities soon after it was issued. Some believed that the stamp could become a rarity and examples of it were sold for as much as 30/-. After a couple of days the stamp once again became available at post offices,<ref name=\"bop1922\"/> and it is no longer scarcer than the other stamps in the issue.<ref name=\"sg\"/> Today, the 1922\u201326 stamps are not rare, and the lower values up to the 2/6 are relatively cheap. The higher values are more expensive,<ref name=\"stampmagazine2019\"/> with the most valuable stamp being the original \u00a31 value of 1922 with a sideways watermark.<ref name=\"sg\"/>\n\n[[File:Malta 1930 AR cover to United States.jpg|thumb|1\u00bdd and 3d Melita stamps with the \"POSTAGE\" overprint used on a 1930 registered cover to the United States. The cover was sent by Rupert Forbes-Bentley, a stamp dealer.<ref name=\"invert\"/>]]\n\nAlthough the 1926 Postage overprints were only on sale for about one week, the bulk of the stamps were sold to stamp dealers and collectors so most of them remain common. However, some values sold out soon after they were issued<ref name=\"gps74\"/> and stamps with the denominations of 4d, 2/-, 2/6 and 5/- are quite expensive today. Since they were only in use briefly, most of the 1926 overprints are more valuable in used condition.<ref name=\"sg\"/> The \"POSTAGE\" overprint has also been [[Philatelic fakes and forgeries|forged]], particularly on the 2/- and 2/6 denominations and on the 3d with inverted overprint.<ref name=\"trory\"/>\n\nThe Malta Study Circle, a group of philatelists who study Malta's stamps and postal history, has produced a number of publications relating to the Melita issue. Two study papers which related to the original 1922\u201326 issue and the 1926 Postage overprints were published in 1970,<ref>{{cite web |title=Melita 1922\u20131926 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112251/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?revHistory=24&category=0 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> and they were combined into a single paper in 1972. A rewritten paper was published in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Study Papers |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112254/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/studypapers/studypapers.asp?pageInfo=2&thisPageSize=20 |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref> The Study Circle's newsletter which is published three times a year is also entitled ''Melita''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |website=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415112257/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/about/information.asp |archivedate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe first set of post-independence Malta definitive stamps, which was issued on 7 January 1965, included an allegorical representation of Melita on the 2/6 denomination which commemorated the [[State of Malta]]. The design by [[Emvin Cremona]] depicts Melita holding a spear and a shield with Malta's 1943\u201364 coat of arms (including the [[George Cross]]), and she is shown sitting among ruins as if after a battle.<ref name=\"sg\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Casingena |first1=Mario |title=Melita |journal=The Melite Post |date=March 2018 |issue=6 |pages=3\u20134 |url=https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/32002/1/The%20Melite%20Post%20-%20Issue%206.pdf |publisher=\u017bejtun Philatelic Society |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200418135622/https://www.um.edu.mt/library/oar/bitstream/123456789/32002/1/The%20Melite%20Post%20-%20Issue%206.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAn allegorical figure with a pose similar to Caruana Dingli's Melita design was used on the fifth and final series of [[Maltese lira]] banknotes. These banknotes were introduced by the [[Central Bank of Malta]] on 18 September 1989, coinciding with the 25th anniversary of independence, and they had four denominations: Lm2, Lm5, Lm10 and Lm20. Another series of banknotes with the same design but with amended security features was issued on 1 June 1994. Versions with signatures of different Governors of the Central Bank were issued in 1997, 1999 and 2001, and there was also a special issue for collectors in 2000.<ref>{{cite book |title=Said Malta Coin & Banknote Catalogue 2010 |date=2010 |publisher=Said International Ltd |pages=180\u2013193}}</ref> These banknotes remained in use until Malta adopted the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, and remained legal tender until 31 January 2008; they were demonetized ten years later on 31 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maltese banknotes \u2013 5th Series and enhanced version (not legal tender after 31 January 2008)|url=http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|publisher=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131227162525/http://www.centralbankmalta.org/site/currency2e.html|archivedate=27 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Timeline Banknotes |url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |website=[[Central Bank of Malta]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122163451/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/timeline-banknotes |archivedate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 December 2011, MaltaPost issued a [[miniature sheet]] containing a \u20ac4.16 stamp to commemorate the 90th anniversary of the establishment of Malta's [[Senate of Malta|Senate]] and [[Parliament of Malta|Legislative Assembly]]. This issue depicted the \u00a31 Melita stamp of 1922 as a [[stamp on stamp]].<ref name=\"maltapost2011\">{{cite news|title=Commemorative Stamp Issue \u2013 90th Anniversary of the Malta Senate and Legislative Assembly|url=https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170316025224/https://www.maltaphilately.com/Content/Images/PDFs/Commemorative%20Stamp%20Issue.pdf|archivedate=16 March 2017|publisher=[[MaltaPost]]|date=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nCaruana Dingli's Melita design was reused for the [[Melita bullion coins]], a series of gold [[bullion coin]]s minted by the Central Bank of Malta in collaboration with [[Lombard Bank]]. The coins were minted in three sizes and denominations (\u20ac25, \u20ac50 and \u20ac100), and were first issued on 30 November 2018. There are plans to mint coins according to demand, retaining the same design except for the year of minting.<ref name=\"cbm-bullion\">{{cite web|title=Melita bullion coins 2018|url=https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|website=[[Central Bank of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121120928/https://www.centralbankmalta.org/en/2018-melita-bullion-coins|archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Postage stamps and postal history of Malta]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |title=Melita 1922\u201326 \u2013 Study Paper 24 |date=1972 |publisher=Malta Study Circle}}\n*{{cite magazine |last1=Pogson |first1=L. V. |title=Malta. 1922. \u00a31. |journal=Melita |volume=1 |issue=1 |url=http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |publisher=Malta Study Circle |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415130044/http://www.maltastudycircle.net/site/userfiles/newsletter/01-01/173-45.pdf |archivedate=15 April 2020}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category inline|Melita issue}}\n\n[[Category:Postage stamps]]\n[[Category:Commemorative stamps]]\n[[Category:Philately of Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 establishments in Malta]]\n[[Category:1922 works]]\n", "name_user": "Xwejnusgozo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSale and collecting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melita_issue"}
{"title_page": "Hichem Rostom", "text_new": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n== Cinema==\n==Tunisian Feature Films==\n* [[1988]]: ''[[Golden Clogs]]'' by [[Nouri Bouzid]]: Mr Youssef\n* [[1989]]: ''[[Layla, my reason]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]: Layla's husband\n* [[1994]]: ''[[The Silences of the palace]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]: Mr Bacheer\n* [[1997]]: ''[[Essa\u00efda]]'' by [[Mohamed Zran]]'': Amine\n* [[1998]]: ''[[Moon wedding]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]\n* [[1999]]: ''[[Grenadine Naps]]'' by [[Mahmoud Ben Mahmoud]]: Wahid Haydar\n* [[2002]]: ''[[The Magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]: Mansour\n* [[2002]]: ''[[The Song of The Noria]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]]: Ali\n* [[2003]]: ''[[The Assassinated Sun]]'' by [[Abdelkrim Bahloul]]: Bramsi\n* [[2004]]: ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]: Hedy\n* [[2006]]: ''[[The TV arrives]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]]: The Director\n* [[2014]]: ''[[The Child of the Sun]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]: Kateb\n* [[2014]]: ''[[Zero!]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]]: The father\n* [[2014]]: ''[[The Last Mirage]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]]: Dr Oussama Saad\n* [[2015]]: ''[[Dicta Shot]]'' by [[Mokhtar Ladjimi]]: Mr Hazem\n* [[2015]]: ''[[Conflict]]'' by [[Moncef Barbouch]]: Mokhtar\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Aleppo Flower]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]: Mourad's father\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Woh!]]by [[Ismahane Lahmar]]: Hmed\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Whispering Sands]]'' by [[Nacer Khemeer]]\n\n==Foreign feature films==\n* [[1976]]: ''[[The Wing or the Thigh]]'' by [[Claude Zidi]]\n* [[1982]]: ''[[Sand blast]]'' by [[Mohammed Lakhdar-Hamina]]\n* [[1991]]: ''[[The Arab Friend]]'' by [[Carmine Fornari]] (Italian)\n* [[1991]]: ''[[Isabelle Eberhardt]]'' by [[Ian Pringle]] (French)\n* [[1992]]: ''[[Massimo Mazzuco's prying goals]]'': Manuel Le Roux\n* [[1993]]: ''[[The Navel of the world]]'' by [[Ariel Zeitoun]]: Costa\n* [[1997]]: ''[[The English Patient]]'' by [[Anthony Minghella]]: Fouad\n* [[1998]]: ''[[Paparazzi]]'' by [[Alain Berberian]]: El Kabouli\n* [[2001]]: ''[[The Desert and the Forest]]'' (plural) by [[Gavin Hood]]: Mahdi\n* [[2008]]: ''[[The Song of the Brides]]'' by [[Karin Albou]]: Raoul's father\n* [[2008]]: ''[[Whatever Lola Wants]]'' by [[Nabil Ayouch]]: Naceur\n* [[2011]]: ''[[The Fifth String]]'' by [[Selma Bergach]]: Amir\n* [[2011]]: ''[[Black Gold]] by [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]]: Colonel Nesibi\n\n==Short films==\n* [[1989]]: ''[[The Trance]] by [[Moncef Dhouib]]\n\n==Dubbing==\n* [[2006]]: ''[[Azur and Asmar]]'' by [[Michel Ocelot]] (Cartoons)\n\n==Television==\n==Tunisian series==\n* [[1991]]: ''[[People are a story]]'' by [[Hamadi Arafa]]\n* [[2002]]: ''[[The Moon of Master Mahrous]]'' by [[Slaheddine Essid]]: A French Lawyer\n* [[2003]]: ''[[A Sun and Shadows]]'' by [[Ezzedine Harbaoui]]: Manoubi El Bransi\n* [[2003]]: ''[[Steps On The Clouds]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]]: His excellence\n* [[2004]]: ''[[Accounts and Penalties]]'' by [[Habib Mselmani]]: Ta\u00efeb\n* [[2005]]: ''[[Caf\u00e9 Jalloul]]'' by [[Lotfi Ben Sassi]] and [[Imed Ben Hamida]]: Chadly\n* [[2005]]: ''[[Money and Wishes]]'' by [[Abdelkader Jerbi]]: Mr Moncef\n* [[2006]]: ''[[Life and Hopes]]'' by [[Mohamed Ghodhbane]]: The police governor\n* [[2006]]: ''[[Today's Genration]]'' by [[Mohamed Damak]]\n* [[2008]]: ''Destiny]]'' by [[Samy Fehri]]:  Mr Hichem Ben Abdullah\n* [[2009]]: ''Find Me A Solution]] (Season 6) by [[Abdelkader Jerbi]]: Dr Lassoued\n* [[2009]]: ''Cages without Birds]]'' by [[Ezzeddine Harbaoui]]: Rachid\n* [[2009]]-[[2011]]: ''[[The Night Stars]]'' (Seasons 1-3) by [[Madih Bela\u00efd]] and [[Mehdi Nasra]]: Chafik\n* [[2010]]: ''[[The Krik Garage]]'' by [[Ridha Bahy]]: Si Ja\u00e2far\n* [[2012]]: ''[[Dipanini]] by [[Hatem Bel Hadj]]\n* [[2013]]: ''[[A Woman's Journal]]'' by [[Najib Ayed]]: Ibrahim\n* [[2014]]: ''[[Destiny]]'' (Season 4) by [[Sami Fehri]]\n* [[2015]]-[[2017]]: ''[[Moufida's Sons]]'' by [[Sami Fehri]]: Sherif\n* [[2015]]: ''[[The Doubt Night]]'' by [[Majdi Smiri]]: Ibrahim\n* [[2015]]:''[[Ambulance]]'' by [[Lassaad Oueslati]]: Mr Taoufik\n* [[2015]]: ''[[Bolice]]'' by [[Majdi Smiri]]\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Bottling]]'' by [[Walid Tayaa]]: Mr Moez\n* [[2016]]: ''[[The Prophet's School]]'' by [[Anouar Ayachi]]: Hichem Ibn Abdelmalik\n* [[2018]]: ''[[Tej El Hadhra]] by [[Sami Fehri]]: Minister [[Mustapha Saheb Ettaba\u00e2]]\n* [[2019]]: ''[[Machair]] by [[Muhammet Gok]]: The flute player and friend of Taher\n\n==Foreign series==\n* [[1992]]: ''[[A Very Special Invitation]]'' (Episode Africa's Money) by [[Vittorio De Sisti]] (Italian)\n* [[1994]]: ''[[The Private War]]'' (Episode Tchao Chicken) by [[Jos\u00e9e Dayan]]\n* [[1998]]: ''[[The Count of Monte-Cristo]]'', mini-series by [[Jos\u00e9e Dayan]]: Muhammad\n* [[1998]]: ''[[Quay n \u00b0 1]] (Episode The Cobras) by [[Pierre Grimblat]] and [[Didier Cohen]]\n* [[2001]]: ''[[Hercule Poirot]]'' by [[Tom Clegg]] (Episode Murder in Mesopotamia): Hotel Receptionist\n* [[2004]]: ''[[The Institute]]'' (Episode 3 of Season 9: Travel diary: Tunisia) by [[G\u00e9rard Klein]]\n* [[2007]]: ''[[Pompei]]'' by [[Giulio Base]]: voice\n* [[2008]]: ''[[House of Saddam]]'' by [[Alex Holmes]], [[Stephen Butchard]] and [[Sally El Hosaini]]: Mohamed Ghani\n* [[2014]]: ''[[Dragunov]]'' by ''[[Osama Rezg]] and [[Siraj Houidi]]: Badi\n* [[2016]]-[[2017]]: ''[[Sir El Morjane]]'' (Moroccan series broadcast on 2M): Mr Habib\n* [[2017]]: ''[[Kabul Kitchen]]'' (Season 3)\n* [[2017]]: ''[[Sir Al Morjane]]''\n\n==TV Movies==\n* [[1987]]: ''[[A Boy named Jesus]]'' (Italian) by [[Franco Rossi]]\n* [[1990]]: ''[[Summer storms, storm warning]]'' by [[Jean Sagols]]: Simon\n* [[1997]]: ''[[A Little Grain of Madness]]'' by [[S\u00e9bastien Grall]]\n* [[2002]]: ''[[Divorce Caprice]]'' (Talak Incha) by [[Moncef Dhouib]]: Khlil\n* [[2003]]: ''[[Amina]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]]\n* [[2011]]: ''[[The Infiltrator]]'' by [[Giacomo Battiato]]: General Ali\n\n==Documentaries==\n* [[2004]]: ''[[Gladiators]]'' by [[Tilman Remme]]: Lanista\n* [[2005]]: ''[[Burn Rome!]]'' by [[Robert Kechichian]]: Hannon\n* [[2005]]: ''[[Empires: Holy Warriors - Richard the Lionheart and Saladin]]'' by [[Richard Bedser]]: Saladin\n* [[2006]]: ''[[The Gospel of Judas]]'' by [[James Barrat for National Geographic]]: The judge\n\n==Other==\n* [[2019]]: Appearance in a music video by [[Maher Zain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Tunisian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image =Hichem Rostom 03.JPG\n| caption = Hichem Rostom in 2015.\n| name         = Hichem Rostom\n| native_name       = \u0647\u0634\u0627\u0645 \u0631\u0633\u062a\u0645\n| native_name_lang  = Arabic\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|5|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Marsa]], [[Tunisia]]\n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = Tunisian\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1987\u2013present\n}}\n\n'''Hichem Rostom''' (born 26 May 1947) is a Tunisian actor of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Festival Tetouan|title=Hommages 2012: Hichem Rostom , Acteur Tunisien|url=http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|accessdate=18 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502142050/http://www.festivaltetouan.org/page.php?134|archivedate=2 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He has appeared in 28 films and television shows since 1987. He starred in ''[[Golden Horseshoes]]'', which was screened in the [[Un Certain Regard]] section at the [[1989 Cannes Film Festival|1989 festival]].<ref name=\"cannes-1989.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/260/year/1989.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Golden Horseshoes |accessdate=2 August 2009|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> He also directed the Carthage Theatre Festival for two sessions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sharmfilmfest.com/index.php/festival/jury/132-hichem-rostom|title=Sharm El-Sheikh Arab & European Film Festival|last=admin|first=sharm|access-date=20 July 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n== Cinema==\n==Tunisian Feature Films==\n* [[1988]]: ''[[Golden Clogs]]'' by [[Nouri Bouzid]]: Mr Youssef\n* [[1989]]: ''[[Layla, my reason]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]: Layla's husband\n* [[1994]]: ''[[The Silences of the palace]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]: Mr Bacheer\n* [[1997]]: ''[[Essa\u00efda]]'' by [[Mohamed Zran]]'': Amine\n* [[1998]]: ''[[Moon wedding]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]\n* [[1999]]: ''[[Grenadine Naps]]'' by [[Mahmoud Ben Mahmoud]]: Wahid Haydar\n* [[2002]]: ''[[The Magic Box]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]: Mansour\n* [[2002]]: ''[[The Song of The Noria]]'' by [[Abdellatif Ben Ammar]]: Ali\n* [[2003]]: ''[[The Assassinated Sun]]'' by [[Abdelkrim Bahloul]]: Bramsi\n* [[2004]]: ''[[Nadia and Sarra]]'' by [[Moufida Tlatli]]: Hedy\n* [[2006]]: ''[[The TV arrives]]'' by [[Moncef Dhouib]]: The Director\n* [[2014]]: ''[[The Child of the Sun]]'' by [[Ta\u00efeb Louhichi]]: Kateb\n* [[2014]]: ''[[Zero!]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]]: The father\n* [[2014]]: ''[[The Last Mirage]]'' by [[Nidhal Chatta]]: Dr Oussama Saad\n* [[2015]]: ''[[Dicta Shot]]'' by [[Mokhtar Ladjimi]]: Mr Hazem\n* [[2015]]: ''[[Conflict]]'' by [[Moncef Barbouch]]: Mokhtar\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Aleppo Flower]]'' by [[Ridha B\u00e9hi]]: Mourad's father\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Woh!]]by [[Ismahane Lahmar]]: Hmed\n* [[2016]]: ''[[Whispering Sands]]'' by [[Nacer Khemeer]]\n\n==Foreign feature films==\n* [[1976]]: ''[[The Wing or the Thigh]]'' by [[Claude Zidi]]\n* [[1982]]: ''[[Sand blast]]'' by [[Mohammed Lakhdar-Hamina]]\n* [[1991]]: ''[[The Arab Friend]]'' by [[Carmine Fornari]] (Italian)\n* [[1991]]: ''[[Isabelle Eberhardt]]'' by [[Ian Pringle]] (French)\n* [[1992]]: ''[[Massimo Mazzuco's prying goals]]'': Manuel Le Roux\n* [[1993]]: ''[[The Navel of the world]]'' by [[Ariel Zeitoun]]: Costa\n* [[1997]]: ''[[The English Patient]]'' by [[Anthony Minghella]]: Fouad\n* [[1998]]: ''[[Paparazzi]]'' by [[Alain Berberian]]: El Kabouli\n* [[2001]]: ''[[The Desert and the Forest]]'' (plural) by [[Gavin Hood]]: Mahdi\n* [[2008]]: ''[[The Song of the Brides]]'' by [[Karin Albou]]: Raoul's father\n* [[2008]]: ''[[Whatever Lola Wants]]'' by [[Nabil Ayouch]]: Naceur\n* [[2011]]: ''[[The Fifth String]]'' by [[Selma Bergach]]: Amir\n* [[2011]]: ''[[Black Gold]] by [[Jean-Jacques Annaud]]: Colonel Nesibi\n\n==Short films==\n* [[1989]]: ''[[The Trance]] by [[Moncef Dhouib]]\n\n==Dubbing==\n* [[2006]]: ''[[Azur and Asmar]]'' by [[Michel Ocelot]] (Cartoons)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDB name|0744599|Hichem Rostom}}\n*{{Commons-inline|Category:Hichem Rostom|Hichem Rostom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rostom, Hichem}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tunisian people of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Tunisian male television actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Tunisian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Tunisian male actors]]\n{{Tunisia-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nesrine1984", "label": "safe", "comment": "rage", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hichem_Rostom"}
{"title_page": "Coney Island Baby", "text_new": "{{about||the 2003 film|Coney Island Baby (film)|the barbershop song|Goodbye, My Coney Island Baby}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Coney Island Baby\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Lou Reed]]\n| cover      = Reed Coney.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 1975 (US)<br>January 19, 1976 (UK)\n| recorded   = October 18\u201328, 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Mediasound, New York City\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]\n| length     = 35:15\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = Lou Reed, [[Godfrey Diamond]]<br /> <small>[[Steve Katz (musician)|Steve Katz]] bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136</small>\n| prev_title = [[Metal Machine Music]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[Rock and Roll Heart]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n'''''Coney Island Baby''''' is the sixth solo [[Album#Studio|studio album]] by [[Lou Reed]], released December 1975 in the USA, and in January 1976 in the UK, by RCA Records.\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:PS 192 4715 18th Av.jpg|thumb|At the end of the title track, Reed dedicates the song to \"all the kids at P.S. 192\", referencing the P.S. 192 \u2013 Magnet School for Math & Science Inquiry, in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], where Reed went to school.]]\n\nThe album has been described by Anthony DeCurtis as \u201cperhaps the most romantic album of Reed\u2019s career.\u201d <ref>{{cite book|last1=DeCurtis|first1=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|publisher=Little Brown|location=New York|isbn=978-0-316-37654-9|page=180}}</ref> Many of the album's songs were inspired by and dedicated to Reed's girlfriend and muse at the time, a [[trans woman]] named Rachel Humphreys.<ref>{{cite book|last1=DeCurtis|first1=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|publisher=Little Brown|isbn=978-0-316-37654-9|page=180}}</ref><ref>https://dangerousminds.net/comments/rachel_lou_reeds_transsexual_muse</ref> According to Aidan Levy, ''Coney Island Baby'' was \"as much a love letter to Rachel as it was to the nostalgic [[Coney Island]] of the mind.\"<ref>Levy, Aidan. Dirty Blvd.: The Life and Music of Lou Reed.Chicago Review Press, 2015</ref> \n\nThe album's title track directly references Rachel with the line: \"I'd like to send this one out to Lou and Rachel, and all the kids at P.S. 192.\" <ref>Lou Reed. \"Coney Island Baby.\" Coney Island Baby, RCA, 1976</ref> \"P.S. 192\" refers to P.S. 192 \u2013 The Magnet School for Math and Science Inquiry, in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]], where Reed went to school before moving to [[Long Island]], NY. <ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/lou-reed-and-coney-island-baby-2013-10?r=US&IR=T Business Insider \u2013 Lou Reed's Most Personal Song About New York Is Not The Same As His Best One 27th October 2013]</ref>. In 1979 Reed said \u201cSaying \u2018I\u2019m a Coney Island baby\u2019 at the end of that song is like saying I haven\u2019t backed off an inch. And don\u2019t you forget it.\u201d<ref>Interview with the Rolling Stone\u2018s Mikal Gilmore in 1979. https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/lou-reed-performs-coney-island-baby-1984-video/</ref><ref>Ref. the 'football coach' lyrics, for Reed's school life see Chapter 3 of Dirty Blvd.: The Life and Music of Lou Reed By Aidan Levy</ref>\n\nThe album includes the song \"She's My Best Friend\", a version of which was originally recorded by Reed's band [[the Velvet Underground]] in 1969, and eventually released on the 1985 [[compilation album]] ''[[VU (album)|VU]]''. The 30th-anniversary re-issue of ''Coney Island Baby'' includes bonus tracks featuring Reed's Velvet Underground bandmate [[Doug Yule]].\n\n==Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| title = Retrospective professional reviews\n| rev1      =  [[AllMusic]] \n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000653089|first=Mark|last=Deming}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}} <ref>[http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=4148 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190822/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=4148 |date=September 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"Kot\">{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=January 12, 1992|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-12/entertainment/9201040209_1_star-rca-robert-quine|title=Lou Reed's Recordings: 25 Years Of Path-breaking Music|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev4Score = B+<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: R|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=R&bk=70|accessdate=March 10, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A1428.htm|title=Coney Island Baby|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n| rev6Score = 7/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev7Score = 3.5/5<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev8      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8Score = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/9477-coney-island-baby/ |title=Lou Reed: Coney Island Baby &#124; Album Reviews |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2006-10-09 |accessdate=2013-12-10}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n| rev10Score = 7/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n}}\nReviewing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1976, [[Paul Nelson (critic)|Paul Nelson]] wrote, \"For the eight superb songs on ''Coney Island Baby'', Reed assembled the best band he has performed with since the Velvet Underground. Michael Suchorsky's versatile, controlled drumming is especially praiseworthy, and Reed himself has even managed to rekindle his intense, individualistic guitar playing of the late Sixties. Better yet, he has shelved his recent FM-DJ vocal style in favor of confident, expressive singing. The songs themselves\u2014as structured and melodic as any Reed has written \u2014 are timeless, terrific rock & roll, and the strength of the genre is accentuated by the simplicity and logic of crisp, tactile production (by Reed and Godfrey Diamond) and careful, resourceful arrangements which emphasize both electric and acoustic guitars and inventive background vocals.\"<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090422123935/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loureed/albums/album/207467/review/5941672/coney_island_baby |title=Lou Reed: Coney Island Baby : Music Reviews : Rolling Stone |first=Paul |last=Nelson |archivedate=2009-04-22 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loureed/albums/album/207467/review/5941672/coney_island_baby |date=1976-03-25 |work=web.archive.org |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981), [[Robert Christgau]] said of the record, \"At first it's gratifying to ascertain that he's trying harder, but very soon that old [[cheapjack]] [[ennui]] begins to poke through. Oddly, though, most of the cheap stuff is near the surface\u2014the songs sound warmer when you listen close. And not even in his most lyrical moments with [[the Velvet Underground|the Velvets]] has he let his soft side show as nakedly as it does on the title cut.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nFor the entry on Reed in ''[[Rough Guides|Rock: The Rough Guide]]'' (1996), Roy Edroso highlighted ''Coney Island Baby'' as \"the most pleasing of Reed's soft-rock albums\" and said, \"His sense of humour has never been better than on 'A Gift', and the title track reminds you why [[Jonathan Richman]] idolized Reed: who else would have had the nerve to try to find 'the glory of love' in the reveries of a troubled would-be high-school football player (in doo-wop style, no less)?\".<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Buckley|editor1-first=Jonathan|editor2-last=Ellingham|editor2-first=Mark|year=1996|chapter=Lou Reed|title=Rock: The Rough Guide|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=1858282012|last=Edroso|first=Roy|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/rockroughguide00buck}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks are written by [[Lou Reed]].\n\n;Side one\n#\"Crazy Feeling\"&nbsp; \u2013 2:56\n#\"Charley's Girl\"&nbsp; \u2013 2:36\n#\"She's My Best Friend\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:00\n#\"Kicks\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:06\n\n;Side two\n#\"A Gift\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:47\n#\"Ooohhh Baby\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:45\n#\"Nobody's Business\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:41\n#\"Coney Island Baby\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:36\n\n===30th Anniversary Deluxe Edition bonus tracks===\n# \"Nowhere at All\" \u2013 3:17 <small>recorded November 18 & 21, 1975 at Mediasound Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Downtown Dirt\" \u2013 4:18 <small>recorded January 3 & 4, 1975 at [[Electric Lady Studios]], NYC</small>\n# \"Leave Me Alone\" \u2013 5:35 <small>recorded October 19 & 20, 1975 at Mediasound Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Crazy Feeling\" \u2013 2:39 <small>recorded January 3 & 4, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"She's My Best Friend\" \u2013 4:08 <small>recorded January 4, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Coney Island Baby\" \u2013 5:41 <small>recorded January 6, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n\n==Personnel==\n* Lou Reed \u2013 vocals, rhythm guitar, piano\n* [[Bob Kulick]] \u2013 lead guitar, slide guitar\n* Bruce Yaw \u2013 bass guitar\n* Michael Suchorsky \u2013 drums, percussion\n* Joanne Vent, Michael Wendroff, [[Godfrey Diamond]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Doug Yule]] \u2013 bass guitar on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136, guitar on bonus tracks 4\u20136\n* Bob Meday \u2013 drums on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136\n* [[Michael Fonfara]] \u2013 keyboards on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136\n;Technical\n*Geoffrey Diamond, Lou Reed, Michael Wendroff \u2013 mixing\n*Jos\u00e9 Rodriguez \u2013 recording\n*Acy Lehman \u2013 art direction\n* [[Mick Rock]] \u2013 photography\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite news |last=Hinckley |first=David |date=5 July 2004 |title=Court and Spark: Boys and Girls Together Down at Coney Island |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/07/05/2004-07-05_court_and_spark__boys_and_gi.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070811131644/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/07/05/2004-07-05_court_and_spark__boys_and_gi.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 August 2007 |newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] }} Mentions the Catalano/Alonzo song.\n\n{{Lou Reed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:1976 albums]]\n[[Category:Lou Reed albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Lou Reed]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Electric Lady Studios]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Mick Rock]]\n[[Category:Transgender-related music]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the 2003 film|Coney Island Baby (film)|the barbershop song|Goodbye, My Coney Island Baby}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Coney Island Baby\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Lou Reed]]\n| cover      = Reed Coney.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = December 1975 (US)<br>January 19, 1976 (UK)\n| recorded   = October 18\u201328, 1975\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Mediasound, New York City\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]\n| length     = 35:15\n| label      = [[RCA Records]]\n| producer   = Lou Reed, [[Godfrey Diamond]]<br /> <small>[[Steve Katz (musician)|Steve Katz]] bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136</small>\n| prev_title = [[Metal Machine Music]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[Rock and Roll Heart]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n'''''Coney Island Baby''''' is the sixth solo [[Album#Studio|studio album]] by [[Lou Reed]], released December 1975 in the USA, and in January 1976 in the UK, by RCA Records.\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n[[File:PS 192 4715 18th Av.jpg|thumb|At the end of the title track, Reed dedicates the song to \"all the kids at P.S. 192\", referencing the P.S. 192 \u2013 Magnet School for Math & Science Inquiry, in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], where Reed went to school.]]\n\nThe album has been described by Anthony DeCurtis as \u201cperhaps the most romantic album of Reed\u2019s career.\u201d <ref>{{cite book|last1=DeCurtis|first1=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|publisher=Little Brown|location=New York|isbn=978-0-316-37654-9|page=180}}</ref> Many of the album's songs were inspired by and dedicated to Reed's girlfriend and muse at the time, a [[trans woman]] named Rachel Humphreys.<ref>{{cite book|last1=DeCurtis|first1=Anthony|title=Lou Reed: A Life|publisher=Little Brown|isbn=978-0-316-37654-9|page=180}}</ref><ref>https://dangerousminds.net/comments/rachel_lou_reeds_transsexual_muse</ref> According to Aidan Levy, ''Coney Island Baby'' was \"as much a love letter to Rachel as it was to the nostalgic [[Coney Island]] of the mind.\"<ref>Levy, Aidan. Dirty Blvd.: The Life and Music of Lou Reed.Chicago Review Press, 2015</ref> \n\nThe album's title track directly references Rachel with the line: \"I'd like to send this one out to Lou and Rachel, and all the kids at P.S. 192.\" <ref>Lou Reed. \"Coney Island Baby.\" Coney Island Baby, RCA, 1976</ref> \"P.S. 192\" refers to P.S. 192 \u2013 The Magnet School for Math and Science Inquiry, in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]], where Reed went to school before moving to [[Long Island]], NY. <ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/lou-reed-and-coney-island-baby-2013-10?r=US&IR=T Business Insider \u2013 Lou Reed's Most Personal Song About New York Is Not The Same As His Best One 27th October 2013]</ref>. In 1979 Reed said \u201cSaying \u2018I\u2019m a Coney Island baby\u2019 at the end of that song is like saying I haven\u2019t backed off an inch. And don\u2019t you forget it.\u201d<ref>Interview with the Rolling Stone\u2018s Mikal Gilmore in 1979. https://faroutmagazine.co.uk/lou-reed-performs-coney-island-baby-1984-video/</ref><ref>Ref. the 'football coach' lyrics, for Reed's school life see Chapter 3 of Dirty Blvd.: The Life and Music of Lou Reed By Aidan Levy</ref>\n\nThe album includes the song \"She's My Best Friend\", a version of which was originally recorded by Reed's band [[the Velvet Underground]] in 1969, and eventually released on the 1985 [[compilation album]] ''[[VU (album)|VU]]''. The 30th-anniversary re-issue of ''Coney Island Baby'' includes bonus tracks featuring Reed's Velvet Underground bandmate [[Doug Yule]].\n\n==Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| title = Retrospective professional reviews\n| rev1      =  [[AllMusic]] \n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000653089|first=Mark|last=Deming}}</ref>\n| rev2      = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}} <ref>[http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=4148 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930190822/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=4148 |date=September 30, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=\"Kot\">{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=January 12, 1992|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-01-12/entertainment/9201040209_1_star-rca-robert-quine|title=Lou Reed's Recordings: 25 Years Of Path-breaking Music|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev4Score = B+<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=1981|title=[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]|publisher=[[Ticknor & Fields]]|isbn=089919026X|chapter=Consumer Guide '70s: R|chapter-url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/get_chap.php?k=R&bk=70|accessdate=March 10, 2019|via=robertchristgau.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/album/A1428.htm|title=Coney Island Baby|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Great Rock Discography]]''\n| rev6Score = 7/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[MusicHound|MusicHound Rock]]''\n| rev7Score = 3.5/5<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev8      = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev8Score = 8.5/10<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/9477-coney-island-baby/ |title=Lou Reed: Coney Island Baby &#124; Album Reviews |publisher=Pitchfork |date=2006-10-09 |accessdate=2013-12-10}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n| rev10 = ''[[Spin Alternative Record Guide]]''\n| rev10Score = 7/10<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n}}\nReviewing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' in 1976, [[Paul Nelson (critic)|Paul Nelson]] wrote, \"For the eight superb songs on ''Coney Island Baby'', Reed assembled the best band he has performed with since the Velvet Underground. Michael Suchorsky's versatile, controlled drumming is especially praiseworthy, and Reed himself has even managed to rekindle his intense, individualistic guitar playing of the late Sixties. Better yet, he has shelved his recent FM-DJ vocal style in favor of confident, expressive singing. The songs themselves\u2014as structured and melodic as any Reed has written \u2014 are timeless, terrific rock & roll, and the strength of the genre is accentuated by the simplicity and logic of crisp, tactile production (by Reed and Godfrey Diamond) and careful, resourceful arrangements which emphasize both electric and acoustic guitars and inventive background vocals.\"<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090422123935/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loureed/albums/album/207467/review/5941672/coney_island_baby |title=Lou Reed: Coney Island Baby : Music Reviews : Rolling Stone |first=Paul |last=Nelson |archivedate=2009-04-22 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/loureed/albums/album/207467/review/5941672/coney_island_baby |date=1976-03-25 |work=web.archive.org |accessdate=3 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies]]'' (1981), [[Robert Christgau]] said of the record, \"At first it's gratifying to ascertain that he's trying harder, but very soon that old [[cheapjack]] [[ennui]] begins to poke through. Oddly, though, most of the cheap stuff is near the surface\u2014the songs sound warmer when you listen close. And not even in his most lyrical moments with [[the Velvet Underground|the Velvets]] has he let his soft side show as nakedly as it does on the title cut.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nFor the entry on Reed in ''[[Rough Guides|Rock: The Rough Guide]]'' (1996), Roy Edroso highlighted ''Coney Island Baby'' as \"the most pleasing of Reed's soft-rock albums\" and said, \"His sense of humour has never been better than on 'A Gift', and the title track reminds you why [[Jonathan Richman]] idolized Reed: who else would have had the nerve to try to find 'the glory of love' in the reveries of a troubled would-be high-school football player (in doo-wop style, no less)?\".<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Buckley|editor1-first=Jonathan|editor2-last=Ellingham|editor2-first=Mark|year=1996|chapter=Lou Reed|title=Rock: The Rough Guide|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|isbn=1858282012|last=Edroso|first=Roy|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/rockroughguide00buck}}</ref>\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks are written by [[Lou Reed]].\n\n;Side one\n#\"Crazy Feeling\"&nbsp; \u2013 2:56\n#\"Charley's Girl\"&nbsp; \u2013 2:36\n#\"She's My Best Friend\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:00\n#\"Kicks\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:06\n\n;Side two\n#\"A Gift\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:47\n#\"Ooohhh Baby\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:45\n#\"Nobody's Business\"&nbsp; \u2013 3:41\n#\"Coney Island Baby\"&nbsp; \u2013 6:36\n\n===30th Anniversary Deluxe Edition bonus tracks===\n# \"Nowhere at All\" \u2013 3:17 <small>recorded November 18 & 21, 1975 at Mediasound Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Downtown Dirt\" \u2013 4:18 <small>recorded January 3 & 4, 1975 at [[Electric Lady Studios]], NYC</small>\n# \"Leave Me Alone\" \u2013 5:35 <small>recorded October 19 & 20, 1975 at Mediasound Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Crazy Feeling\" \u2013 2:39 <small>recorded January 3 & 4, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"She's My Best Friend\" \u2013 4:08 <small>recorded January 4, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n# \"Coney Island Baby\" \u2013 5:41 <small>recorded January 6, 1975 at Electric Lady Studios, NYC</small>\n\n==Personnel==\n* Lou Reed \u2013 vocals, rhythm guitar, piano\n* [[Bob Kulick]] \u2013 lead guitar, slide guitar\n* Bruce Yaw \u2013 bass guitar\n* Michael Suchorsky \u2013 drums, percussion\n* Joanne Vent, Michael Wendroff, [[Godfrey Diamond]] \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Doug Yule]] \u2013 bass guitar on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136, guitar on bonus tracks 4\u20136\n* Bob Meday \u2013 drums on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136\n* [[Michael Fonfara]] \u2013 keyboards on bonus tracks 2, 4\u20136\n;Technical\n*Geoffrey Diamond, Lou Reed, Michael Wendroff \u2013 mixing\n*Jos\u00e9 Rodriguez \u2013 recording\n*Acy Lehman \u2013 art direction\n* [[Mick Rock]] \u2013 photography\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* {{cite news |last=Hinckley |first=David |date=5 July 2004 |title=Court and Spark: Boys and Girls Together Down at Coney Island |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/07/05/2004-07-05_court_and_spark__boys_and_gi.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070811131644/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/2004/07/05/2004-07-05_court_and_spark__boys_and_gi.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 August 2007 |