{{cite web|url=http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=810&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2014&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |title=ONORIFICENZE \u2013 2006 |website=quirinale.it |language=Italian |date=12 December 2006 |accessdate=19 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110195241/http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/Onorificenze.aspx?pag=810&qIdOnorificenza=&cognome=&nome=&daAnno=1800&aAnno=2014&luogoNascita=&testo=&ordinamento=2 |archivedate=10 January 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Marco Materazzi}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.marcomaterazzi.it}}\n* [http://www.inter.it/aas/squadra/player1?codgioc=G0717&L=en&stagione=2006/07 Official Inter profile]\n* [http://www.footballdatabase.com/site/players/index.php?dumpPlayer=99 Profile and stats] from Football Database\n\n{{navboxes colour\n|title=Italy squads\n|bg= #0066bc\n|fg= #FFFFFF\n|list1=\n{{Italy squad 2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Italy squad UEFA Euro 2004}}\n{{Italy squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Italy squad UEFA Euro 2008}}\n}}\n{{Serie A Defender of the Year}}\n{{Indian Super League winning managers}}\n{{Chennaiyin FC managers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Materazzi, Marco}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Italian people of Sardinian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Lecce]]\n[[Category:Italian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football central defenders]]\n[[Category:Carpi F.C. 1909 players]]\n[[Category:A.C. Perugia Calcio players]]\n[[Category:Everton F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan players]]\n[[Category:Chennaiyin FC players]]\n[[Category:Serie B players]]\n[[Category:Serie D players]]\n[[Category:Serie C players]]\n[[Category:Serie A players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2004 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2008 players]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup-winning players]]\n[[Category:Violence in sports]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League head coaches]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in India]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Italian association football player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Marco Materazzi\n| image       = Marco Materazzi - Inter Mailand (1).jpg\n| image_size  = 230\n| caption     = Materazzi in 2009\n| fullname    = Marco Materazzi\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1973|8|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lecce]], Italy \n| height      = {{height|m=1.93}}\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = 1988\u20131990 |youthclubs1 = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n| youthyears2 = 1990\u20131991 |youthclubs2 = [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina Peloro]]\n| youthyears3 = 1991\u20131993 |youthclubs3 = Tor di Quinto\n| years1      = 1990\u20131991 |clubs1      = [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]]                    |caps1 = 1    |goals1  = 0\n| years2      = 1991\u20131993 |clubs2      = Tor di Quinto                                 |caps2  = 12  |goals2  = 0\n| years3      = 1993\u20131994 |clubs3      = [[S.C. Marsala|Marsala]]                      |caps3  = 25  |goals3  = 4\n| years4      = 1994\u20131995 |clubs4      = [[Trapani Calcio|Trapani]]                    |caps4  = 13  |goals4  = 2\n| years5      = 1995\u20131998 |clubs5      = [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]]                    |caps5  = 47  |goals5  = 7\n| years6      = 1996\u20131997 |clubs6      = \u2192 [[Carpi FC 1909|Carpi]] (loan)              |caps6  = 18  |goals6  = 7\n| years7      = 1998\u20131999 |clubs7      = [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]                      |caps7  = 25  |goals7  = 1\n| years8      = 1999\u20132001 |clubs8      = [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]]                    |caps8  = 51  |goals8  = 15\n| years9      = 2001\u20132011 |clubs9      = [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]]                |caps9  = 184 |goals9  = 18\n| years10     = 2014      |clubs10     = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]                  |caps10 = 7   |goals10 = 0\n| totalcaps = 405\n| totalgoals = 55\n| nationalyears1 = 2001\u20132008 \n| nationalteam1  = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]        \n| nationalcaps1  = 41\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| manageryears1       = 2014\u20132016\n| managerclubs1       = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]] ([[Player-coach|player-manager]])\n| club-update         = \n| nationalteam-update = \n| medaltemplates = {{MedalSport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{Flagcountry|ITA|2003}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n}}\n'''Marco Materazzi''' {{postnominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Ufficiale OMRI]]}} ({{IPA-it|\u02c8marko mate\u02c8rattsi}}; born 19 August 1973) is an [[Italians|Italian]] former professional [[Association football|footballer]] and [[Association football manager|manager]].\n\nEarly in his career, Materazzi played with various Italian teams in [[Serie B]] and [[Serie C]], and with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the [[Premier League]]. He spent two periods with [[Perugia Calcio|Perugia]] (1995\u201398 and 1999\u20132001) and signed for [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] in 2001 for \u20ac10&nbsp;million. At club level, he won a number of major honors with Inter, including five [[Serie A]] league titles in a row from 2006 to 2010, one [[UEFA Champions League]], one [[FIFA Club World Cup]], four [[Coppa Italia]] titles, and the [[Supercoppa Italiana]] four times.<ref>The Matrix \u2013 Marco Materazzi: {{cite web|url=http://lazymanscalcio.tumblr.com/post/18215957095/the-matrix |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203063129/http://lazymanscalcio.tumblr.com/post/18215957095/the-matrix |archivedate=3 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi earned 41 caps for Italy from his debut in 2001 until 2008, playing in two World Cups and two European Championships. He was one of the key players in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final]] against France, as he scored Italy's goal and later, in extra time, he received a headbutt from [[Zinedine Zidane]], who was punished with a red card.<ref name=\"World Cup\"/> Italy then went on to win the World Cup in a penalty shoot-out, during which Materazzi scored again.\n\nA controversial and provocative figure in football, he was known for his very physical and aggressive style of play as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]], as well as his tight marking and strong, harsh tackling, which led him to receive more than 60 yellow cards and 25 red cards throughout his playing career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.serpentsofmadonnina.com/2011/7/18/3211758/marco-materazzi-a-bandieria-among-bandierie|title=Marco Materazzi: A Bandieria Among Bandierie|publisher=Serpents of Madonnina|date=18 July 2011|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019164000/https://www.serpentsofmadonnina.com/2011/7/18/3211758/marco-materazzi-a-bandieria-among-bandierie|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to his temper and his heavy challenges, he has been involved in several altercations with other players during matches,<ref name=\"Materazzi\">{{cite web|last1=Cazullo|first1=Aldo|title=Materazzi|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2006/luglio/11/Materazzi_co_9_060711008.shtml|website=www.corriere.it|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|accessdate=14 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914092029/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2006/luglio/11/Materazzi_co_9_060711008.shtml|archive-date=14 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> drawing comparisons with retired defender [[Pasquale Bruno]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Emanuele Gamba|title=\"O' animale resto sempre io una volta aspettai Lerda...\"|trans-title=\"I'm still the animal once I waited for Lerda...\"|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/brunotunnel/brunotunnel/brunotunnel.html|publisher=La Repubblica|accessdate=4 May 2015|language=Italian|date=3 February 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701222541/http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/brunotunnel/brunotunnel/brunotunnel.html|archive-date=1 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Times]]'' placed Materazzi at number 45 in their list of the 50 hardest footballers in history.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 50 Hardest Footballers |url=http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851 |accessdate=14 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019002225/http://www.empireonline.com/forum/printable.asp?m=1554851 |archivedate=19 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nMaterazzi began his footballing career with the [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] and then the [[F.C. Messina Peloro|Messina Peloro]] youth teams from 1990 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.alpha59.it/news/50/la-carriera-di-marco-materazzi.html|title=LA CARRIERA DI MARCO MATERAZZI|date=3 March 2018|publisher=alpha59.it|access-date=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205559/https://www.alpha59.it/news/50/la-carriera-di-marco-materazzi.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He spent his early career in the lower divisions of Italian football, with amateur side Tor di Quinto (1991\u201392), [[Serie C]]2 team [[S.C. Marsala 1912|Marsala]] (1993\u201394), and Serie C1 [[A.S.D. Trapani Calcio|Trapani]] (1994\u201395), where he narrowly missed a historic promotion to [[Serie B]] after losing a promotion playoff to [[S.S. Gualdo|Gualdo]]. [[Serie B]] squad [[Perugia Calcio]] signed Materazzi for the first time in 1995,<ref name=\"Early life\"/> but he spent a part of the 1996\u201397 season in Serie C with [[Carpi F.C. 1909|Carpi]].\n\nHe then spent 1998\u201399 with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toffeeweb.com/players/profiles/Materazzi.php|title=Marco Materazzi central defender|publisher=ToffeeWeb.com|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091427/https://www.toffeeweb.com/players/profiles/Materazzi.php|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> where he was sent off three times in just 27 games, and scored twice, against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in the league<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-barmby-sparks-everton-deluge-1071633.html|title=Barmby sparks Everton deluge|publisher=[[The Independent]]|author=Neil Bramwell|location=London|date=17 February 1999|accessdate=9 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313043242/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-barmby-sparks-everton-deluge-1071633.html|archive-date=13 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Huddersfield Town F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-dacourt-drives-everton-through-1200301.html|title=Dacourt drives Everton through|publisher=The Independent|author=Phill Shaw|location=London|date=23 September 1998|accessdate=9 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313050323/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-dacourt-drives-everton-through-1200301.html|archive-date=13 March 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=gazzetta/>\n\nHe then returned to Perugia in 1999 and scored 12 goals, including 7 from penalties in the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]], breaking [[Daniel Passarella]]'s Serie A record of most goals by a defender in one season.<ref name=gazzetta/>\n\n===Internazionale===\n====2001\u20132004: Debut and controversies====\n[[File:Materazzi maglia.jpg|thumb|Materazzi's number 23 shirt]]\nMaterazzi was signed by [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]] in July 2001 for \u20ac10 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200107/17/3b54a7f001fa6/|title=Difensore cannoniere all'Inter|trans-title=The goalscoring defender at Inter|publisher=Rai Sport|language=Italian|date=17 July 2001|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205554/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200107/17/3b54a7f001fa6/|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportspundit.com/soccer/players/107-marco-materazzi|title=Marco Materazzi|website=Sports Pundit|access-date=29 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013212026/https://www.sportspundit.com/soccer/players/107-marco-materazzi|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He took squad number 23 and made his competitive debut for the club on 26 August in the opening [[2001\u201302 Serie A|championship]] match against [[A.C. Perugia|Perugia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/inteperu/inteperu/inteperu.html|title=Kallon e Vieri da favola, decolla l'Inter di Cuper|trans-title=Kallon and Vieri fairytale, Cuper's Inter takes off|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|date=26 August 2001|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013172548/http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/inteperu/inteperu/inteperu.html|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi's first goal for Inter came only in his second appearance, netting inside 10 minutes in a 2\u20132 draw at [[Parma Calcio 1913|Parma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/parmainter/parmainter/parmainter.html|title=Il Tardini si conferma, campo stregato per l'Inter|trans-title=The Tardini is confirmed as cursed field for Inter|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|date=9 September 2001|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304222015/http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/parmainter/parmainter/parmainter.html|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He also played eight time in the [[2001\u201302 UEFA Cup|season]]'s [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]], with the debuting match coming on 20 September in the 3\u20130 win versus [[Romania]]'s [[SR Bra\u0219ov|Bra\u0219ov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2001/matches/round=1551/match=68273/index.html|title=Internazionale 2-0 Bra\u0219ov|publisher=UEFA.com|date=20 September 2001|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181013172256/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2001/matches/round=1551/match=68273/index.html|archive-date=13 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi played 23 matches in league, including the final decisive match versus [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]] which lost Inter the championship title;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/maggio/06/Inter_paga_grande_illusione_ga_0_0205061470.shtml|title=L' Inter paga la grande illusione|trans-title=Inter pays great illusion|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=6 May 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190103231056/http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/maggio/06/Inter_paga_grande_illusione_ga_0_0205061470.shtml|archive-date=3 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> he was a protagonist of a controversy episode following the final whistle as he was included in a heated discussion with the opposite players which also went to physical confrontation.<ref name=\"Materazzi23\">{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/materazzi/materazzi/materazzi.html|title=Materazzi, lite con Nesta: \"Vi ho fatto vincere il titolo\"|trans-title=Materazzi, quarrel with Nesta: \"I won you the title\"|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|date=6 May 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205712/http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/materazzi/materazzi/materazzi.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/maggio/06/Moratti_prende_con_Lazio_ga_0_0205061424.shtml|title=Moratti se la prende con la Lazio|trans-title=Moratti gets angry with Lazio|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=6 May 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002635/http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2002/maggio/06/Moratti_prende_con_Lazio_ga_0_0205061424.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was caught by the cameras shouting at Lazio captain [[Alessandro Nesta]], saying: \"I won you the title\", in reference to Perugia's win over [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 2000 which lead Lazio to the title.<ref name=\"Materazzi23\"/>\n\nIn the [[2002\u201303 Inter Milan season|following season]], Materazzi made 33 appearances across all competitions, including 13 in [[UEFA Champions League]], where he played his first match on 14 August 2002 in a goalless draw against [[Sporting CP]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1635/match=70011/index.html|title=Sporting CP 0-0 Internazionale|publisher=UEFA.com|date=14 August 2002|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221223533/http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1635/match=70011/index.html|archive-date=21 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi's [[2003\u201304 Inter Milan season|2003\u201304 season]] was highlighted by injuries, such as the one he suffered on 25 November during the 5\u20131 home loss to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group B|UEFA Champions League group stage]] which kept him out of action for two months.<ref name=\"Suspension\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=129970.html#inter+miss+materazzi|title=Inter to miss Materazzi|publisher=UEFA.com|date=27 November 2003|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015114705/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=129970.html#inter+miss+materazzi|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was in the center of a controversy again in the beginning of 2004 for aggression towards Siena player [[Bruno Cirillo]]. This happened on 1 February in a match which was won 4\u20130 by Inter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/serie-a/match-report/2003-04/UNICO/UNI/19/INTSIE|title=Inter 4-0 Robur Siena|publisher=Lega Serie A|language=Italian|date=1 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> Materazzi (who did not play in the match) confronted Cirillo in the dressing rooms and begun spewing insults towards him. He also punched him in the face, fracturing his lip.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2004/febbraio/02/Materazzi_dato_pugno__ga_10_040202066.shtml|title=\"Materazzi mi ha dato un pugno\"|trans-title=\u00abMaterazzi gave me a punch\u00bb|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Graziano Mirko|author2=Capone Antonello|date=2 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002537/http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2004/febbraio/02/Materazzi_dato_pugno__ga_10_040202066.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/matestangata/matestangata/matestangata.html|title=Cirillo: \"Prima gli insulti, poi il pugno\", Materazzi rischia una lunga squalifica|trans-title=Cirillo: \"First the insults, then the punch\", Materazzi risks a long disqualification|publisher=Reppublica.it|language=Italian|location=Milan|date=2 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205616/http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/matestangata/matestangata/matestangata.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> After the incident was denounced, the sports judge Maurizio Laudi suspended Materazzi until 29 March,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/primi_piani/calcio/2004/pp_1.0.289804258.shtml|title=Materazzi fermo fino al 29 marzo|trans-title=Materazzi suspended until 29 March|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|location=Milan|date=3 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529060318/http://www.gazzetta.it/primi_piani/calcio/2004/pp_1.0.289804258.shtml|archive-date=29 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> meaning that he will miss eight club matches and one international match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/campionato-italiano/2003-2004/materazzi-in-brawl_sto541746/story.shtml|title=Materazzi faces ban for post-match brawl|publisher=Eurosport|work=Reuters|date=2 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042336/https://www.eurosport.com/football/campionato-italiano/2003-2004/materazzi-in-brawl_sto541746/story.shtml|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/materazzi-i-was-provoked|title=Materazzi: I was provoked|publisher=The World Game|date=22 April 2014|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042040/https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/materazzi-i-was-provoked|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to his domestic suspension, Materazzi was also suspended by [[UEFA]] for two [[UEFA Cup]] games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=147670.html|title=Materazzi suspended for UEFA Cup|publisher=UEFA.com|date=24 February 2004|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015120056/https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=147670.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Inter was also fined with \u20ac5,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/marzo29/marzo29/marzo29.html|title=Materazzi fermo fino ad aprile, 5000 euro di multa all'Inter|trans-title=Materazzi suspended until April, 5000 euro fine for Inter|publisher=Reppublica.it|language=Italian|date=3 February 2004|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205707/http://www.repubblica.it/2004/b/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/marzo29/marzo29/marzo29.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi later apologized for the incident, saying that he \"behaved badly\" and \"reacted in a bad way\", also adding that he would not appeal the suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11860/2290669/materazzi-apologises-to-cirillo|title=Materazzi apologises to Cirillo|publisher=Sky Sports|author=Nadia Carminati|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015042352/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11860/2290669/materazzi-apologises-to-cirillo|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====2004\u20132008: Domestic success under Mancini====\nIn July 2004, at the start of [[2004\u201305 Inter Milan season|2004\u201305 season]], Inter bench was entrusted to manager [[Roberto Mancini]], with whom \u2013 in the first season \u2013 Materazzi lost his place in the starting lineup.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2005/01/07/mancini-ok-materazzi-non-voleva-insultare-me.html|title=Mancini: Ok Materazzi, non voleva insultare me|trans-title=Mancini: Ok Materazzi, he did not want to insult me|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|location=Livorno|date=7 January 2005|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015115108/https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2005/01/07/mancini-ok-materazzi-non-voleva-insultare-me.html|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the next season he played more,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://it.eurosport.com/calcio/amichevoli/2005/funziona-la-doppia-inter_sto747019/story.shtml|title=Funziona la doppia Inter|trans-title=Inter double works|publisher=Eurosport|language=Italian|date=27 July 2005|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002514/https://it.eurosport.com/calcio/amichevoli/2005/funziona-la-doppia-inter_sto747019/story.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and was the only Italian to score a goal for the club that season. On 5 March 2006, Materazzi scored an 89th-minute header at [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] to rescue his side a point and to break the hosts' record of 11 consecutive victories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/c/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/28giornata/romainter/romainter.html|title=Materazzi beffa la Roma al 90', Sfuma la dodicesima vittoria|trans-title=Materazzi mocked Roma at 90 ', Wastes the twelfth victory|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|location=Rome|date=5 March 2006|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205902/http://www.repubblica.it/2006/c/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/28giornata/romainter/romainter.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/22097/materazzi-earns-inter-point-in-rome|title=Materazzi earns Inter point in Rome|publisher=inter.it|date=5 March 2006|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015114607/https://www.inter.it/en/news/22097/materazzi-earns-inter-point-in-rome|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He finished the 2005\u201306 season by totaling 39 appearances across all competitions.\n\nMaterazzi signed a new contract in August 2006 which kept him at [[San Siro]] until June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-08-04/materazzi-extends-inter-contract/1230522|title=Materazzi extends Inter contract|publisher=ABC News|date=3 August 2006|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028144627/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2006-08-04/materazzi-extends-inter-contract/1230522|archive-date=28 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> At the end of the year he was a nominee for [[UEFA Team of the Year]] along with teammate [[Fabio Grosso]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/24907/uefa-team-of-2006-grosso-matrix-on-list|title=UEFA team of 2006: Grosso, Matrix on list|publisher=inter.it|date=6 December 2006|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015114553/https://www.inter.it/en/news/24907/uefa-team-of-2006-grosso-matrix-on-list|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[2006\u201307 Serie A|2006\u201307 season]] saw him scoring 10 goals, thus being the top scoring defender of Serie A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/stats/scorers/_/league/ita.1/year/2006/italian-serie-a?cc=5901|title=Italian Serie A Goal Scoring Leaders \u2013 2006\u201307 \u2013 ESPN FC<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> He notably scored in the 4\u20133 win in [[Derby della Madonnina]] against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Milan/Primo_Piano/2006/10_Ottobre/28/prederby.shtml|title=Milan-Inter 3-4|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|location=Milan|date=28 October 2006|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002624/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Milan/Primo_Piano/2006/10_Ottobre/28/prederby.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> an overhead kick versus [[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]] and a brace away to [[AC Siena|Siena]] on 23 April which won the club's 15th league title with five games remaining.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/12/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-16/inter-messina/inter-messina.html|title=Materazzi inventa la rovesciata, l'Inter firma un bel record|trans-title=Materazzi invents the overhead kick, Inter sign a good record|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|location=Milan|date=17 December 2006|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205905/http://www.repubblica.it/2006/12/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-16/inter-messina/inter-messina.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Andersson|first=Astrid|title=Materazzi secures early title for Inter|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/2311629/Materazzi-secures-early-title-for-Inter.html|accessdate=23 April 2014|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=23 April 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915120327/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/2311629/Materazzi-secures-early-title-for-Inter.html|archive-date=15 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> For his performances, Materazzi was voted the [[Serie A Defender of the Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/28510/materazzi-wins-footballers-association-award|title=Materazzi wins footballers' association award|publisher=inter.it|date=29 January 2008|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015114610/https://www.inter.it/en/news/28510/materazzi-wins-footballers-association-award|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marco Materazzi - Inter Mailand (2).jpg|thumb|right|240px|Materazzi during a training session]]\nMaterazzi missed the first part of [[2007\u201308 Inter Milan season|2007\u201308 season]] due to an injury suffered whilst on international duty which forced him to be sidelined until November 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/11/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-13/inter-atalanta/inter-atalanta.html|title=Inter, Suazo e Cruz fanno tutto facile, Poi l'Atalanta mette paura: 2-1|trans-title=Inter, Suazo and Cruz make everything easy, then Atalanta puts fear: 2-1|publisher=Reppublica.it|language=Italian|location=Milan|date=24 November 2007|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205832/http://www.repubblica.it/2007/11/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-13/inter-atalanta/inter-atalanta.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later in February of the following year, Materazzi gave a poor display in the first leg of [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League]] first knockout round against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], receiving a red card in the 30th minute, as Inter lost 2\u20130 at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/liverpool-vs-inter/97342|title=Late show eases Rafa pressure|publisher=Sky Sports|author=James Dall|date=20 February 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165312/https://www.skysports.com/football/liverpool-vs-inter/97342|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His performance was criticised by his teammates after the end of the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2292303/Inter-Milan-players-turn-on-Marco-Materazzi.html|title=Inter Milan players turn on Marco Materazzi|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk|author=Malcolm Moore|location=Rome|date=21 February 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165231/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2292303/Inter-Milan-players-turn-on-Marco-Materazzi.html|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Later on throughout the season, during a 2\u20132 draw against [[Robur Siena|Siena]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2008/05/11/692352/inter-siena-2-2-nerazzurri-raggiunti-per-due-volte-e|title=Inter-Siena 2-2: Nerazzurri raggiunti per due volte. E Materazzi sciupa il penalty-scudetto|trans-title=Inter-Siena 2-2: Nerazzurri reached twice. And Materazzi wastes the penalty-Scudetto|publisher=Goal.com|date=11 May 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014170636/http://www.goal.com/it/news/2/serie-a/2008/05/11/692352/inter-siena-2-2-nerazzurri-raggiunti-per-due-volte-e|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi argued with striker [[Julio Ricardo Cruz]] on whom to take a penalty kick.<ref name=\"The penalty\"/> Eventually it was Materazzi who took it but his attempt was easily saved by [[Alex Manninger]].<ref name=\"The penalty\"/> It was his first miss since 2001. The draw spoiled Inter's chances of winning the title with one game to spare. After the match, the choice to take the penalty was criticized by manager [[Roberto Mancini]] while Materazzi himself apologized, stating that it should have been Cruz the one to take it.<ref name=\"The penalty\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-33527620080512|title=Inter's Materazzi apologises for taking penalty|publisher=Reuters.com|date=12 May 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014170555/https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-33527620080512|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Inter eventually won the championship for the third consecutive time after defeating Parma 2\u20130 in the last matchday with Materazzi playing full-90 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/19/internazionale.europeanfootball|title=Inter's blushes spared as Ibrahimovic earns his redemption|publisher=The Guardian|date=19 May 2008|accessdate=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518174411/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/19/internazionale.europeanfootball|archive-date=18 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2008/05/18/italy/serie-a/parma-fc/fc-internazionale-milano/501458/|title=Parma vs. Internazionale 0 \u2013 2|publisher=Soccerway|date=18 May 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014170601/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2008/05/18/italy/serie-a/parma-fc/fc-internazionale-milano/501458/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He concluded the season with 23 Serie A appearances, 4 Coppa Italia appearances, 1 Supercoppa Italiana appearance and 3 UEFA Champions League appearances for a total of 33 appearances.\n\n====2008\u20132011: Final years and more glory====\nThe summer of 2008 saw the arrival of Portuguese manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] who did not see Materazzi as the first choice in defence, relegating him to the bench.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2009/05/speciale/altri/inter-vince-scudetto/pagellone-scudetto/pagellone-scudetto.html|title=Julio Cesar e Maicon fondamentali, Cambiasso decisivo, bene Santon|trans-title=J\u00falio C\u00e9sar and Maicon fundamental, Cambiasso decisive, Santon good|publisher=Repubblica.it|language=Italian|author=Gianni Piva|date=17 May 2009|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180909192709/http://www.repubblica.it/2009/05/speciale/altri/inter-vince-scudetto/pagellone-scudetto/pagellone-scudetto.html|archive-date=9 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Apart from that, his season was also marred by injuries, which reduced his league tally to only 8 appearances.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1707/inter/2008/12/10/1004791/marco-materazzi-fractures-cheekbone|title=Inter Defender Materazzi Fractures Cheekbone|publisher=Goal.com|author=Adam Scime|date=10 December 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014204000/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1707/inter/2008/12/10/1004791/marco-materazzi-fractures-cheekbone|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored his first UEFA Champions League goal on 4 November in a 3\u20133 draw at [[Anorthosis Famagusta FC|Anorthosis]] in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group B|Group B]] matchday 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/30190/champions-league-anorthosis-3-3-inter|title=Champions League: Anorthosis 3-3 Inter|publisher=inter.it|date=4 November 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165311/https://www.inter.it/en/news/30190/champions-league-anorthosis-3-3-inter|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1716/champions-league/2008/11/04/948412/player-ratings-anorthosis-3-3-inter|title=Player Ratings: Anorthosis 3-3 Inter|publisher=Goal.com|author=Anthony Sormani|date=4 November 2008|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014203958/http://www.goal.com/en/news/1716/champions-league/2008/11/04/948412/player-ratings-anorthosis-3-3-inter|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi won his 4th [[Serie A|championship]] on 17 May 2009 following Inter's 3\u20130 defeat of Siena.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2009/may/18/serie-a-inter-jose-mourinho|title=Jose Mourinho makes Ibrahimovic sweat for his goal as Inter celebrate scudetto in style|publisher=The Guardian|author=Paolo Bandini|date=18 May 2009|accessdate=14 October 2018}}</ref> Despite playing rarely, he was still praised by president [[Massimo Moratti]] who said that Materazzi \"always played well whenever he was called upon last season\" while manager Mourinho stated that he wanted to have Materazzi in his team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=837298.html#/evergreen+materazzi+extends+inter+stay|title=Evergreen Materazzi extends Inter stay|publisher=UEFA.com|date=10 June 2009|accessdate=15 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160505111017/http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=837298.html#/evergreen+materazzi+extends+inter+stay|archive-date=5 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Marco Materazzi - Inter Mailand (3).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Materazzi in action for Inter]]\nIn June 2009, Materazzi was handed a new deal by Inter until June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/inter.milan.materazzi.motta/index.html|title=Veteran Materazzi handed new Inter deal|publisher=CNN|date=2 July 2009|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091314/http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/07/02/inter.milan.materazzi.motta/index.html|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was used sparingly during the [[2009\u201310 Inter Milan season|2009\u201310 season]], making 20 appearances in all competitions. In January 2010, he underwent arthroscopic surgery to repair damage to the medial meniscus in his right knee which kept him sidelined for one month.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=941521.html|title=Materazzi leaves hole in Inter defence|publisher=UEFA.com|date=11 January 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091334/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=941521.html|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi was an injury-time substitute for Inter in the [[2010 UEFA Champions League Final]] against [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], replacing [[Diego Milito]] who scored both of their goals in the 2\u20130 victory in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/33968/champions-league-final-bayern-munich-0-2-inter|title=Champions League final: Bayern Munich 0-2 Inter|publisher=inter.it|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091410/https://www.inter.it/en/news/33968/champions-league-final-bayern-munich-0-2-inter|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to that, Inter also clinched the ''[[Scudetto]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/86/italy/2010/05/16/1927554/siena-0-1-inter-diego-milito-secures-scudetto-for-nerazzurri|title=Siena 0-1 Inter: Diego Milito Secures Scudetto For Nerazzurri|publisher=Goal.com|author=Adam Scime|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625185226/http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/86/italy/2010/05/16/1927554/siena-0-1-inter-diego-milito-secures-scudetto-for-nerazzurri|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> for the fifth season in a row,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/16/inter-milan-win-serie-a|title=Internazionale take fifth successive Serie A title with win at Siena|publisher=The Guardian|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009211602/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/may/16/inter-milan-win-serie-a|archive-date=9 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[2010 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/2177/coppa-italia/2010/05/06/1910660/inter-1-0-roma-diego-milito-wins-the-coppa-italia-for-the|title=Inter 1-0 Roma: Diego Milito Wins The Coppa Italia For The Nerazzurri|publisher=Goal.com|author=Subhankar Mondal|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507132645/http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/2177/coppa-italia/2010/05/06/1910660/inter-1-0-roma-diego-milito-wins-the-coppa-italia-for-the|archive-date=7 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> to complete the [[Treble (association football)|Treble]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1490968.html|title=Inter join exclusive treble club|publisher=UEFA.com|date=22 May 2010|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091347/https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1490968.html|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe begun the [[2010\u201311 Inter Milan season|2010\u201311 season]] by coming on in the last minutes of a 3\u20131 home win over [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] in the [[Supercoppa Italiana]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1516658.html|title=Two-goal Eto'o fires Inter to more glory|publisher=UEFA.com|date=22 August 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207192216/http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1516658.html|archive-date=7 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi's first league match of the season came later in November where he started in the derby against Milan due to the absence of [[Walter Samuel]]; he conceded a penalty in 4th minute for fouling [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]] and was later sent to hospital after a receiving a kung-fu kick in the stomach by the Swede.<ref name=\"Injury1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/3194/video/2010/11/15/2214843/video-zlatan-ibrahimovic-sends-marco-materazzi-to-hospital|title=VIDEO: Zlatan Ibrahimovic Sends Marco Materazzi To Hospital With A Kung-Fu Kick|publisher=Goal.com|date=15 November 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014204002/http://www.goal.com/en/news/3194/video/2010/11/15/2214843/video-zlatan-ibrahimovic-sends-marco-materazzi-to-hospital|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2010/m=11/news=materazzi-taken-hospital-after-ibra-clash-1334644.html|title=Materazzi taken to hospital after Ibra clash|publisher=FIFA.com|date=15 November 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165128/https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/news/y=2010/m=11/news=materazzi-taken-hospital-after-ibra-clash-1334644.html|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Inter lost the match 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/11/14/italy/serie-a/fc-internazionale-milano/ac-milan/990066/|title=Internazionale vs. Milan 0 \u2013 1|publisher=Soccerway|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014171929/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2010/11/14/italy/serie-a/fc-internazionale-milano/ac-milan/990066/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Following the end of the match, manager [[Rafael Ben\u00edtez]] calmed the situation by stating that Materazzi's injury \"doesn't seem serious\".<ref name=\"Injury1\"/> He returned in action two weeks later by playing full-90 minutes in a 5\u20132 home win over Parma.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/news/35129|title=Inter-Parma: 5-2, Stankovic starts and finishes|publisher=inter.it|date=29 November 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014204146/https://www.inter.it/en/news/35129|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In December, Materazzi was included in Inter's squad for [[2010 FIFA Club World Cup]], remaining on the bench as Inter won their 5th title of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=254488/match=300140542/match-report.html|title=Internazionale on top of the world|publisher=FIFA.com|date=18 December 2010|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625052030/https://www.fifa.com/clubworldcup/matches/round=254488/match=300140542/match-report.html|archive-date=25 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi left the club in July 2011 after not being offered a new contract, having played around 270 games for the club and winning 15 trophies,<ref name=\"inter.it\"/> and shortly after, announced his retirement from the sport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/materazzi-inter/|title=Report: Materazzi leaving Inter after season|publisher=Sportsnet.ca|date=20 June 2011|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091256/https://www.sportsnet.ca/soccer/materazzi-inter/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://intermilanfansworldwide.wordpress.com/2011/07/21/a-salute-to-marco-materazzi-tutti-pazzi-per-materazzi/|title=A Salute to Marco Materazzi|publisher=Inter fans|date=21 July 2011|accessdate=13 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091653/https://intermilanfansworldwide.wordpress.com/2011/07/21/a-salute-to-marco-materazzi-tutti-pazzi-per-materazzi/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He was later appointed in the role of ambassador to Inter. Later, Materazzi accused manager [[Leonardo Ara\u00fajo|Leonardo]] of \"stabbing him in the back\" and being the reason for his departure from Inter,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italian-football/2011/07/20/2583194/marco-materazzi-hits-out-at-former-inter-coaches-leonardo-rafael-|title=Marco Materazzi hits out at former Inter coaches Leonardo & Rafael Benitez|publisher=Goal.com|author=Salvatore Landolina|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014204136/http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italian-football/2011/07/20/2583194/marco-materazzi-hits-out-at-former-inter-coaches-leonardo-rafael-|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2012/04/22/3053177/leonardo-stabbed-me-in-the-back-two-or-three-times-claims|title=Leonardo stabbed me in the back two or three times, claims Materazzi|publisher=Goal.com|author=Mark Doyle|date=22 April 2012|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181015002852/http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2012/04/22/3053177/leonardo-stabbed-me-in-the-back-two-or-three-times-claims|archive-date=15 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and also threw accusations to president Massimo Moratti of not having defended him against Leonardo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2011/luglio/20/MATERAZZI_tradito_Leonardo_ora_Inter_ga_10_110720426.shtml|title=MATERAZZI \"Io tradito da Leonardo ma ora l' Inter l' ho tatuata sul cuore\"|trans-title=Materazzi \u00abI was betrayed by Leonardo and now I have Inter tattoed in my heart\u00bb|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author=Elefante Andrea|date=20 July 2011|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825002638/http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2011/luglio/20/MATERAZZI_tradito_Leonardo_ora_Inter_ga_10_110720426.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Chennaiyin FC===\n[[File:Marco materazzi CFC 2014-2016.jpg|thumb|210px|right|Materazzi during his time with Chennaiyin FC.]]\nOn 22 September 2014, Materazzi was signed as the player-manager of [[Chennaiyin FC]] in the [[2014 Indian Super League season|inaugural season]] of the [[Indian Super League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fans accord Marco Materazzi a warm welcome|url=http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/389-fans-accord-marco-materazzi-a-warm-welcome|publisher=ISL|accessdate=22 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922193812/http://www.indiansuperleague.com/news/389-fans-accord-marco-materazzi-a-warm-welcome|archive-date=22 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi signed a two-season contract with Chennaiyin for $1 million (USD) every season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Elano is Chennai\u00b4s Marquee|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/Elano-is-Chennais-Marquee/2014/09/19/article2438488.ece|publisher=INDIAN Express|accessdate=19 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921044922/http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/Elano-is-Chennais-Marquee/2014/09/19/article2438488.ece|archive-date=21 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Marco Materazzi to manage Chennai Titans|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Marco-Materazzi-to-manage-Chennai-Titans/articleshow/42334829.cms|publisher=Times of  India|accessdate=12 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915133420/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Marco-Materazzi-to-manage-Chennai-Titans/articleshow/42334829.cms|archive-date=15 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi did not choose himself to play in their opening match, a 2\u20131 victory at [[FC Goa]] on 15 October courtesy of a free kick from marquee player and former Brazil international [[Elano]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Raj|first1=Rohan|title=ISL: Record-breaking Chennaiyin FC romp to 2\u20131 win over FC Goa|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-chennaiyin-fc-vs-fc-goa-live-indian-super-league-match-4-nehru-stadium/1/395917.html|accessdate=15 October 2014|work=[[India Today]]|date=15 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015231348/http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/isl-chennaiyin-fc-vs-fc-goa-live-indian-super-league-match-4-nehru-stadium/1/395917.html|archive-date=15 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Six days later in his first home game, Chennaiyin defeated the [[Kerala Blasters]] 2\u20131, but four days after that he lost for the first time, 1\u20134 to the [[Delhi Dynamos]]. In the club's fourth match of the season, he selected himself to play for the first time, starting in a 5\u20131 win over [[Mumbai City FC|Mumbai City]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Suchindran|first1=Aravind|title=Elano, Mendoza shine as Chennai trounce Mumbai 5\u20131|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Elano-Mendoza-shine-as-Chennai-trounce-Mumbai-5-1/articleshow/44967343.cms|accessdate=31 October 2014|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=28 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030235633/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/indian-super-league/top-stories/Elano-Mendoza-shine-as-Chennai-trounce-Mumbai-5-1/articleshow/44967343.cms|archive-date=30 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 November, he brought his former international defensive partner Alessandro Nesta out of retirement to play for Chennaiyin until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davies|first1=Jack|title=Alessandro Nesta comes out of retirement to join Indian Super League side Chennaiyin|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2014/11/28/6601801/alessandro-nesta-comes-out-of-retirement-to-join-indian|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=Goal.com|date=28 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141130144711/http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2892/transfer-zone/2014/11/28/6601801/alessandro-nesta-comes-out-of-retirement-to-join-indian|archive-date=30 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Chennaiyin finished the 14-game regular season in first place in the league, with Materazzi having made 6 appearances. In the [[2014 Indian Super League finals|end-of-season play-offs]], the team were eliminated in extra time in the semi-finals by the [[Kerala Blasters]].\n\nAt the end of the [[2015 Indian Super League season|2015 season]], in which Materazzi led Chennaiyin to the Indian Super League championship, his contract ended.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ready to extend contract: Materazzi|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/football/indian-super-league-2015-finals-isl-2015-finals-ready-to-extend-contract-chennaiyin-fc-head-coach-materazzi/article8011414.ece|accessdate=21 December 2015|work=The Hindu|date=21 December 2015}}</ref> After the conclusion of the [[2016 Indian Super League season|2016 season]], it was announced that Materazzi would not return to the club for 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chennaiyin Statement|url=http://chennaiyinfc.com/chennaiyin-fc-club-statement-on-marco-materazzi/|accessdate=6 March 2017|work=Chennaiyin FC|date=6 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307050450/http://chennaiyinfc.com/chennaiyin-fc-club-statement-on-marco-materazzi/|archive-date=7 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Debut and 2002 World Cup===\nMaterazzi made his debut for the [[Italy national football team|Italy national team]] on 25 April 2001, in a 1\u20130 friendly match victory against [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/1294939.stm|title=Italy edge out South Africa|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 April 2001|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324142800/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/1294939.stm|archive-date=24 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He made two appearances in the qualifying campaign against Georgia and Hungary. In the final tournament of the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]], Materazzi was used as a reserve player to back up Alessandro Nesta and Fabio Cannavaro. He made only one appearance by coming on as a substitute for Nesta in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group G|2\u20131 loss]] to [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] in the group stage but soon in the 90th minute Materazzi played a floating ball over the top from just over half way to [[Filippo Inzaghi|Inzaghi]] but everyone missed the ball and it rolled in the back of the net but the goal was disallowed after referee [[Graham Poll]] claimed that Inzaghi had grabbed an opponent's shirt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/09/worldcupfootball2002.sport23|title=Italy are offline|publisher=The Guardian|author1=Simon Kuper|date=9 June 2002|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222091740/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/09/worldcupfootball2002.sport23|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi was later criticised for his defending on both of Croatia's goals during the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/italy_v_croatia/default.stm|title=Croatia punish Italy|publisher=BBC|date=8 June 2002|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306122711/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/italy_v_croatia/default.stm|archive-date=6 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/itacrpag/itacrpag/itacrpag.html|title=Male Materazzi e Maldini, Non brilla Totti, bene Vieri|trans-title=Materazzi and Maldini bad, Totti does not shine, Vieri good|publisher=Reppublica.it|language=Italian|author=Massimo Vincenzi|date=8 June 2002|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909190504/http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/itacrpag/itacrpag/itacrpag.html|archive-date=9 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 2004===\nDespite a long suspension with Inter,<ref name=\"Suspension\"/> Materazzi was still called up by manager [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] for the [[UEFA Euro 2004]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldsoccer.com/news/trapattoni-names-italy-squad-for-euro-2004-55531|title=Trapattoni names Italy squad for EURO 2004|publisher=World Soccer|date=19 May 2004|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020053109/https://www.worldsoccer.com/news/trapattoni-names-italy-squad-for-euro-2004-55531|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> where he was on the bench for Italy's first two games but started in the final [[UEFA Euro 2004 Group C#Italy vs Bulgaria|group game]] against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in place of the suspended [[Fabio Cannavaro]], as Italy came from behind to win 2\u20131; in the first half, Materazzi was judged to have allegedly fouled [[Dimitar Berbatov]] in the area, conceding a penalty, which [[Martin Petrov]] subsequently converted. Despite the win, Italy were eliminated in the first round on direct encounters, following a three-way five point tie with [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787525.stm|title=Italy 2\u20131 Bulgaria|publisher=BBC|date=23 June 2004|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190518185149/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787525.stm|archive-date=18 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi played his first match as captain for Italy on 17 November 2004 in a 1\u20130 friendly win over [[Finland national football team|Finland]] in which he also received a yellow card.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=2688|title=Football MATCH: 17.11.2004 Italy v Finland|publisher=EU-Football.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020060208/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=2688|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His second and final match as captain came in another friendly against [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] on 30 March 2005 where he played in the first half.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=3097|title=Football MATCH: 30.03.2005 Italy v Iceland|publisher=EU-Football.info|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801155233/https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=3097|archive-date=1 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2006 World Cup===\n[[File:Marco Materazzi.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Materazzi in 2006, during the FIFA World Cup in Germany]]\nMaterazzi was included in the 23-man squad by manager [[Marcelo Lippi]] for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] which was his third major tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2006/0515/204699-italy/|title=Lippi names Italy 23 for Germany|publisher=rte.ie|date=14 June 2007|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020053028/https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2006/0515/204699-italy/|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He began the tournament as a reserve player, but after [[Alessandro Nesta]] suffered an injury in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup - Group E#Czech Republic vs Italy|group match]] against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/26/worldcup2006.sport9|title=Business as usual for Italy despite concern over Nesta|publisher=The Guardian|author=Russell Thomas|date=26 June 2006|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020094956/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/jun/26/worldcup2006.sport9|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Materazzi came on as his replacement and made an impact by scoring a goal, and was named Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853358.stm|title=Czech Republic 0\u20132 Italy|publisher=BBC|date=22 June 2006|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222162421/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853358.stm|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He received a red card in the round of 16 match against [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] for a foul on [[Mark Bresciano]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/football/italy-legend-marco-materazzi-discusses-2006-world-cup-in-exclusive-interview-for-fox-sports/news-story/4bd76b9c83f41df117058b4df05ccfc9?sv=f96affe74ac5765f10211b71df50184b|title=Italy legend Marco Materazzi discusses 2006 World Cup in exclusive interview for Fox Sports|publisher=Fox Sports|date=26 August 2012|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> which ended in a 1\u20130 win for the Italians, and was suspended for the quarter-final against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], which Italy won 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991534.stm|title=Italy 1\u20130 Australia|publisher=BBC|date=26 June 2006|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105221857/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991534.stm|archive-date=5 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]] against [[France national football team|France]], Materazzi fouled [[Florent Malouda]] to concede a penalty, which [[Zinedine Zidane]] subsequently scored. He made another impact by scoring a goal to tie the game, a header from a right sided corner by [[Andrea Pirlo]]. After the match went to extra-time, Materazzi and Zidane were involved in a confrontation in the 110th minute, where Materazzi verbally insulted Zinedine Zidane while tugging his shirt as Zidane attempted to walk away, which ended with [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final#Provocation of Zidane analysis|Zidane headbutting]] Materazzi and receiving a red card.<ref name=\"report\">{{cite web |url= https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/matches/match/97410064/|title=Italy \u2013 France |website=FIFA.com |publisher=F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Football Association |accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/mar/11/world-cup-moments-zinedine-zidane-head-butt|title=World Cup stunning moments: Zinedine Zidane's head-butt|publisher=The Guardian|author=Ian McCourt|date=25 March 2018|accessdate=20 October 2018}}</ref> The game then continued to penalties. Materazzi scored Italy's second penalty as they defeated France 5\u20133 to claim their fourth FIFA World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991652.stm|title=Italy 1\u20131 France (aet)|publisher=BBC|author1=Jonathan Stevenson|date=9 July 2006|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502060415/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991652.stm|archive-date=2 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> After the final, the confrontation resulted in a major controversy as Zidane accused Materazzi of insulting his sister and mother. Additionally, Materazzi claimed that after he had grabbed Zidane's jersey, Zidane sarcastically said to him ''\"If you want my shirt, I will give to you afterwards\"''. Materazzi then revealed that he replied, ''\"Preferisco la puttana di tua sorella<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/08/sezioni/sport/calcio/frase-materazzi/frase-materazzi/frase-materazzi.html|title=Materazzi-Zidane, mistero svelato Ecco la frase che scaten\u00f2 la testata - Calcio - Sport - Repubblica.it|website=www.repubblica.it|access-date=26 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130605190717/http://www.repubblica.it/2007/08/sezioni/sport/calcio/frase-materazzi/frase-materazzi/frase-materazzi.html|archive-date=5 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\"'' (''I would prefer your whore of a sister<ref name=autogenerated1 />''), which resulted in the head-butt.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=378084&cc=5901|title=Materazzi reveals details of Zidane World Cup slur|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=5 September 2006|accessdate=2 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090405025125/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=378084&cc=5901 |archivedate=5 April 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"World Cup\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/aug/18/newsstory.sport2|title=And Materazzi's exact words to Zidane were...|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|date=18 August 2007|accessdate=18 March 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140212053652/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/aug/18/newsstory.sport2|archive-date=12 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Three British [[tabloid newspaper]]s, the ''[[Daily Star (United Kingdom)|Daily Star]]'', the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'', alleged that Materazzi had called Zidane ''\"the son of a terrorist whore.\"'' Materazzi took legal action against all three newspapers and the allegations were later withdrawn.<ref>Tryhorn, Chris (2008-04-07). [https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/apr/07/pressandpublishing.medialaw Zidane headbutt victim wins Star apology] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927191853/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/apr/07/pressandpublishing.medialaw |date=27 September 2016 }}. ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved on 2009-02-09.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/feb/06/marco-materazzi-zinedine-zidane-the-sun-libel Materazzi wins British libel damages over Sun's claims about Zidane headbutt]. ''[[The Guardian]]'' (2009-02-06). Retrieved on 2009-02-09.</ref> FIFA later issued a [[Swiss franc|CHF]] 5,000 fine and a two-match ban against Materazzi. Alongside striker [[Luca Toni]], Materazzi was Italy's top scorer throughout the tournament with two goals; he also won 14 challenges throughout the competition.<ref name=simpatia>{{cite web|url=http://www.blitzquotidiano.it/sport/italia-2006-campioni-del-mondo-grosso-jolly-cannavaro-buffon-voto-simpatia-75-1883864/|title=Home Sport  Italia 2006: campioni del mondo. Grosso jolly, Cannavaro e Buffon muro: voto simpatia 7,5|publisher=BlitzQuotidiano.it|language=Italian|author1=Antonio Sansonetti|date=6 June 2014|accessdate=3 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223321/http://www.blitzquotidiano.it/sport/italia-2006-campioni-del-mondo-grosso-jolly-cannavaro-buffon-voto-simpatia-75-1883864/|archive-date=23 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===UEFA Euro 2008===\nUnder Roberto Donadoni, Materazzi appeared consistently during the Euro 2008 qualifying campaign and became a starter after Alessandro Nesta's retirement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28769420070801|title=Italy's Nesta retires from international game|publisher=Reuters.com|author=Mark Meadows|location=Milan|date=1 August 2007|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020094952/https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28769420070801|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the [[UEFA Euro 2008]] tournament,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/28/italy.euro2008.squad|title=Italy squad for Euro 2008|publisher=The Guardian|date=28 May 2008|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180705151545/https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/28/italy.euro2008.squad|archive-date=5 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> he started in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group C#Netherlands vs Italy|3\u20130 loss]] to the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] but was substituted in the 54th minute in what would later prove to be his final appearance for Italy, as he was replaced later in the tournament by [[Giorgio Chiellini]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/09/euro2008.euro2008groupc2|title=Euro 2008: Holland v Italy \u2013 as it happened|publisher=The Guardian|author1=Paolo Bandini|date=10 June 2008|accessdate=14 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222135346/http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/09/euro2008.euro2008groupc2|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, after Lippi's return, Materazzi was not called in the national team again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2008/07/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/lippi-presenta/prime-convocazioni/prime-convocazioni.html|title=Lippi richiama Gilardino e si tiene Del Piero|trans-title=Lippi recalls Gilardino and has Del Piero|publisher=Reppublica.it|author=Gianluca Moresco|location=Rome|date=16 August 2008|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180824205855/http://www.repubblica.it/2008/07/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/lippi-presenta/prime-convocazioni/prime-convocazioni.html|archive-date=24 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> He totaled 41 appearances and 2 goals for Italy.<ref name=\"EU-Football.info\"/>\n\n==Style of play==\nAn aggressive, physical, and hard-tackling [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]], who was also known for his tight marking of opponents,<ref name=\"Materazzi\"/> Materazzi was considered to be one of the best defenders of his generation, and was highly regarded by two of the world's most respected coaches, [[Marcello Lippi]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]], later becoming close friends with both managers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.futaa.com/football/article/why-i-cried-when-jose-left--materazzi |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904083401/http://www.futaa.com/football/article/why-i-cried-when-jose-left--materazzi |archivedate=4 September 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Materazzi was lauded by his managers in particular for being a goal threat as a defender, due to his outstanding aerial ability, which made him dangerous during set pieces.<ref name=\"gazzetta\"/> His prolific goalscoring allowed him to capture the record for most goals in a Serie A season by a defender, which was broken during the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|2000\u201301 season]].<ref name=gazzetta>{{cite web|title=I difensori e il vizio del gol Facchetti il top, poi Matrix|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/26-10-2009/i-difensori-vizio-gol--601754131334.shtml|accessdate=14 September 2014|language=Italian|work=[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007231235/http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/26-10-2009/i-difensori-vizio-gol--601754131334.shtml|archive-date=7 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He was also an accurate set piece and penalty kick taker, with a powerful shot from distance.<ref name=\"gazzetta\"/> In addition to these attributes, he had solid technical skills and reliable distribution, and was known for frequently playing long balls to the strikers.<ref name=\"Materazzi\"/> During his time with Internazionale, he developed the nickname ''Matrix''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?N=43308&L=it|title=Foto: Marco Materazzi, Matrix|publisher=inter.it|date=26 December 2008|accessdate=19 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calciogazzetta.it/altro/la-storia-di-un-campione-trattata-da-calcio-gazzetta/storie-di-calcio-marco-matrix-materazzi/|title=[Storie di Calcio] Marco \"Matrix\" Materazzi|trans-title=[Stories of Football] Marco \u201cMatrix\u201d Materazzi|publisher=calciogazzetta.it|language=Italian|date=21 June 2017|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020094937/http://www.calciogazzetta.it/altro/la-storia-di-un-campione-trattata-da-calcio-gazzetta/storie-di-calcio-marco-matrix-materazzi/|archive-date=20 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMarco Materazzi was born in [[Lecce]], where his father, [[Giuseppe Materazzi|Giuseppe]], a professional footballer, was playing for [[U.S. Lecce]].<ref name=\"Early life\">{{cite web|url=https://thesefootballtimes.co/2018/09/10/the-violence-and-victory-of-marco-materazzi/|title=The violence and the victory of Marco Materazzi|publisher=These Football Times|author=Christopher Weir|date=10 September 2018|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014091338/https://thesefootballtimes.co/2018/09/10/the-violence-and-victory-of-marco-materazzi/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Giuseppe was also a former football coach and manager of teams such as [[Pisa Calcio|Pisa]], [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], [[Sporting Clube de Portugal|Sporting CP]] and [[Tianjin Teda F.C.|Tianjin Teda]]. Materazzi's mother died when he was 15 years old.<ref name=\"Early life\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.90min.com/posts/4866847-marco-materazzi-reveals-what-he-said-to-zinedine-zidane-before-2006-world-cup-final-headbutt|title=Marco Materazzi Reveals What He Said to Zinedine Zidane Before 2006 World Cup Final Headbutt|date=14 April 2017|website=90min.com|access-date=29 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629150857/https://www.90min.com/posts/4866847-marco-materazzi-reveals-what-he-said-to-zinedine-zidane-before-2006-world-cup-final-headbutt|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/07/materazzi-zidane-headbutt-world-cup-2006|title=Materazzi finally admits what he said to Zidane in the World Cup Final|date=9 July 2016|publisher=|access-date=29 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190629150859/https://ftw.usatoday.com/2016/07/materazzi-zidane-headbutt-world-cup-2006|archive-date=29 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His sister, Monia married Maurizio Maestrelli, the son of former manager [[Tommaso Maestrelli]]; Maurizio died on 28 November 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcinter1908.it/in-evidenza/il-calcio-piange-maurizio-maestrelli/|title=Il calcio piange Maurizio Maestrelli|trans-title=The football mourns Maurizio Maestrelli|publisher=fcinter1908.it|language=Italian|author=Lorenzo Roca|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180322/http://www.fcinter1908.it/in-evidenza/il-calcio-piange-maurizio-maestrelli/|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> His brother Matteo is a [[sports agent]].\n\nAs stated by his father, Marco grew up a supporter of Lazio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tifonet.it/notizie/materazzi-e-i-tifosi-laziali-amore-finito-22311|title=Materazzi e i tifosi laziali: amore finito?|trans-title=Materazzi and Lazio fans: finished love?|publisher=tifo-net.it|language=Italian|date=14 May 2007|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825180205/http://www.tifonet.it/notizie/materazzi-e-i-tifosi-laziali-amore-finito-22311|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2007, he released his autobiography called \"Una vita da guerriero\" (The Life of a Warrior) published by journalists Andrea Elefante (from ''[[La Gazzetta dello Sport|Gazzetta dello Sport]]'') and Roberto De Ponti (from ''[[Corriere della Sera]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2007/08_Agosto/31/Libromatbis.shtml|title=Materazzi si racconta in un libro|trans-title=Materazzi told in a book|publisher=La Gazetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=8 August 2007|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825212554/https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Inter/Primo_Piano/2007/08_Agosto/31/Libromatbis.shtml|archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMaterazzi was married on 23 June 1997 to Daniela, with whom he has three children: Anna, Davide and Gianmarco.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golssip.it/wags/calciatori-in-famiglia/marco-materazzi-un-anniversario-davvero-speciale-21-anni-di-matrimonio/|title=Marco Materazzi, un anniversario davvero speciale: \"21 anni di matrimonio\"|trans-title=Marco Materazzi, a really special anniversary: \"21 years of marriage\"|publisher=Golssip.it|language=Italian|date=23 June 2018|accessdate=18 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004161521/http://www.golssip.it/wags/calciatori-in-famiglia/marco-materazzi-un-anniversario-davvero-speciale-21-anni-di-matrimonio/|archive-date=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/it/news/30777/materazzi-a-raggi-x-io-e-i-miei-figli|title=Materazzi a 'Raggi X': \"Io e i miei figli\"|trans-title=Materazzi to Raggi X: Me and my children|publisher=inter.it|language=Italian|date=28 December 2005|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826004949/https://www.inter.it/it/news/30777/materazzi-a-raggi-x-io-e-i-miei-figli|archive-date=26 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\nSource:<ref name=\"inter.it\">{{cite web|url=https://www.inter.it/en/archivio_giocatore/G0717|title=Marco Materazzi|publisher=inter.it|accessdate=19 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181019205532/https://www.inter.it/en/archivio_giocatore/G0717|archive-date=19 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Soccerway\">{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/coaches/marco-materazzi/59/|title=Italy \u2013 M.Materazzi \u2013 Profile with news, career statistics and history|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=25 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222164314/http://int.soccerway.com/coaches/marco-materazzi/59/|archive-date=22 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=person&id=59|title=Marco Materazzi|publisher=Scoresway|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014130133/http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=person&id=59|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcio.com/profilo_giocatori/marco-materazzi/|title=Marco Materazzi|publisher=Calcio.com|accessdate=14 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014130202/http://www.calcio.com/profilo_giocatori/marco-materazzi/|archive-date=14 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Club statistics\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[A.C.R. Messina|Messina]]\n|[[1990\u201391 Serie B|1990\u201391]]\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Serie B]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Tor di Quinto\n|1991\u201392\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Serie D]]\n|0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0\n|-\n|1992\u201393\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||12||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!12!!0!!0!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2